<HEAD>Officials Say Spanish Duke's Skiing Death Was An Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 10-11 bgng `But defending' with six grafs to UPDATE
with sheriff refusing to make statement about safety violations, describing
how victim received and acknowledged a warning. Picks up 12th graf pvs,
`Knous said...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLEN MILLER HADDOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VAIL, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials of the World Alpine Ski Championships maintained Tuesday that no safety violations contributed to the death of a cousin of <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s king, but a champion skiier suggested the victim was on a closed course. The Duke of <LOCATION> Cadiz </LOCATION>, a 52-year-old first cousin of King <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> and member of the international governing body of ski racing, was killed Monday at the <ORGANIZATION> Beaver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Creek </ORGANIZATION> ski resort when he ran into a cable being raised to hold a finish-line banner for the men's downhill course <PERSON> Alfonso </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON> <PERSON> y </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Dampierre </PERSON> suffered neck lacerations and apparently died instantly, <LOCATION> Eagle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Coroner <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> Meineke </PERSON> said. An official cause of death had not been released by Tuesday afternoon. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON> was at one-time married to the granddaughter of Spanish dictator <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Franco </PERSON>. Although he was not in the line of succession to the <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> throne, he was a descendant of <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> XIV </PERSON>, the French <PERSON> Sun </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, and was the Bourbon or `` legitimist'' candidate for king had the monarchy ever been restored in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. King <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> and Queen <LOCATION> Sofia </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> expressed their sorrow over his death. `` There is no reason to believe that any safety violations occurred,'' <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Knous </PERSON>, president of the championships' organizing committee, told a news conference Tuesday. `` It truly appears that this was an accident, a very, very unfortunate and tragic incident,'' <PERSON> Knous </PERSON> said. Sheriff A.J. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> would not say Tuesday night whether <LOCATION> Eagle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> officials agree with <PERSON> Knous </PERSON>. `` We will make no conclusions about safety violations, not until the investigation is done,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. `` I will discuss the investigation with the district attorney. Until then, we are looking at all possibilities.'' But defending world downhill champion <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> said the victim and other ski officials ignored normal procedures when they skied down a closed course. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, who said his investigation would take a month, confirmed that the course was closed, but said, `` We believe he -LRB- de <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON> -RRB- had the authority to be on there.'' <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON> was skiing Monday with companions when he hit the cable as course workers were moving the finish line and banners uphill from the end of the slalom course to the end of the downhill. Witnesses said one of the companions, former Austrian Olympic champion <PERSON> Toni </PERSON> <PERSON> Sailer </PERSON>, saw the cable and warned <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON>, who acknowledged the warning but still slammed into it at neck level, according to <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Knous </PERSON> said there were no safety violations despite the fact that the course was closed following an inspection by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ski </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, known by its French initials as <ORGANIZATION> FIS </ORGANIZATION>. Also there were no banners or identifying material on the cable that the duke hit. He said he could n't comment on whether the duke and his skiing companions should have been on the course at the time. <PERSON> Mueller </PERSON>, 31, one of the favorites in Saturday's race, said: `` Normally, when we prepare for a competition, the course is closed. But here, the <ORGANIZATION> FIS </ORGANIZATION> is skiing down for pleasure. I think that's a big mistake. If the downhill course is closed, it should be closed for all people.'' Downhill training went on as scheduled Tuesday although social events were canceled or postponed. Officials of the championships wore black armbands, and flags throughout the ski resort flew at half-staff. The Spanish ski team, which had been training at another <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> ski resort, still planned to come to <LOCATION> Vail </LOCATION> and compete, <PERSON> Knous </PERSON> said. The championship meet continues through this weekend. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON> served as <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s ambassador to <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> from 1969 to 1973, was president of the <ORGANIZATION> Spanish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Skiing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> from 1977 to 1984 and an eight-time Spanish skiing champion. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON>'s father was the elder brother of King <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON>' father Both men's fathers were the sons of King <PERSON> Alfonso </PERSON> <PERSON> XIII </PERSON>, who abdicated the Spanish throne in 1931. The duke married <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> <PERSON> Franco </PERSON> in 1972 and they divorced in 1982. In February 1984, the older of his two sons was killed in an auto accident in which de <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON> was driving. A judge ruled that <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON> had been negligent and stripped him of the custody of his other son. <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez-Ochoa </PERSON>, the slalom gold medalist at the 1972 Olympics and a close friend of the duke, said <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON> liked to `` ski fast and drive fast.'' Referring to the duke's divorce, the fatal auto accident and the skiing tragedy, <PERSON> Fernandez-Ochoa </PERSON> described the victim as `` an unlucky person. Bad things happened to him.''
