<SECOND>PM-Panda Dies,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ying-Ying, Mexico's Prolific Panda Mother, Dead At Age 14</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The giant panda Ying-Ying, the female of the pair that made <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s panda breeding program the most successful outside <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, has died of unknown causes _ possibly a broken heart _ at age 14. <PERSON> Ying-Ying </PERSON>, who died late Sunday, had been depressed since October, about three months after Pe-Pe, her mate, died of cancer, said <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Elena </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON>, director of the Chapultepec Zoo. She said <PERSON> Ying-Ying </PERSON> had been ill for several days. `` We do n't what she died of,'' Ms. <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> said. `` The autopsy did n't determine the cause'' but zoo officials hope laboratory tests will determine the cause. She said <PERSON> Ying-Ying </PERSON> had until Pe-Pe's death spent every day with the panda <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> sent as a gift in 1975, when <PERSON> Ying-Ying </PERSON> was 11 months old. `` She did n't want to live without Pe-Pe,'' Ms. <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> said. `` She was very much in love with Pe-Pe. She did n't want to go out into the garden. She ate but not as well as she used to. `` She was n't as aggressive, as sure of herself. Before she would n't let you touch her and recently it did n't matter to her.'' Giant pandas are an endangered species and only about 18 are in captivity outside <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The animals generally have a life expectancy of about 20 years. <PERSON> Ying-Ying </PERSON>, who was nearly 15, gave birth to seven offspring after natural mating with Pe-Pe. Four survived. <PERSON> Ying-Ying </PERSON> accidentally rolled onto the first cub eight days after its birth in 1980, crushing it, and one each of two sets of twins died. <PERSON> Tohui </PERSON>, the oldest of the four surviving offspring, set off panda mania when she was born July 21, 1981, and is the zoo's hope for continuing to produce more pandas. In December, the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoo </ORGANIZATION> sent its 16-year-old male panda to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> in hopes the two would mate. Ms. <PERSON> Hoyo </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ying-Ying </PERSON>'s body, like Pe-Pe's, will be stuffed and put on display.
