<SECOND>PM-Open Enrollment,0807</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blemishes Surface In Open Enrollment System Hailed By Reagan, Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN IRON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has called free choice `` the single most promising idea'' in education. But he'd get an argument from <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> and others involved in the nation's most comprehensive application of the concept. `` I do n't know if anyone can say it is off to a good start,'' said <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON>, superintendent of a school district on northern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>'s Iron Range. `` We're very close to being out of business.'' The problem is that nearly a third of the district's 1,000 students have applied to attend school in neighboring <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, next year. The exodus is possible because of a statewide open enrollment program that will give all public school students freedom to choose where they attend school. <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON>'s district stands in contrast to the affluent public schools in <LOCATION> Edina </LOCATION>, a predominantly white district in suburban <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>. Two districts do not take outsiders: <LOCATION> Sartell </LOCATION>, because it is crowded; and <LOCATION> Edina </LOCATION>, because it voted not to take part in the open enrollment program. Critics say the open enrollment program wo n't reach the poor, penalizes small towns, invites inter-school athletic recruiting, leaves some districts with inappropriate staffing levels, and provides dissident parents an extortion tool to use on school boards. Others hail the program for promoting excellence. At a White House Workshop on Choice in Education on Jan. 10, former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> referred to open enrollment as `` that marvelous program in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> that is fostering unprecedented competition among public schools to make them more attractive to parents and students.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> are not the only admirers of the plan, which encourages free market-type competition among public schools. <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, enrollment options specialist with the <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said the program will probably `` weed out'' lackluster schools. Gov. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> said the program makes the state `` a national leader in empowering families to make choices about their children's education. But not all state officials are convinced. `` Based on the limited experience we've had in this state, it's ridiculous,'' said state Rep. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> McEachern </PERSON>, chairman of the state <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Only 435 of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>'s 740,000 grade school and high school students applied for the program this year and applications for next year have reached 1,300. The program applies to school districts of more than 1,000 students, and will be extended to all school districts by the 1990-91 school year. Districts now have the option of voting not to participate. `` It's a choice for the rich,'' <PERSON> McEachern </PERSON> insisted. `` That's all. In Mountain Iron and <PERSON> Buhl </PERSON>, communities still recovering from the collapse of the taconite industry a decade ago, parents have been divided over which school buildings to close in the aftermath of a merger. Open enrollment has been an escape route from conflict, <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> said. The lower enrollment wo n't cut operating expenses, but it will reduce state aid by $ 1.2 million, a third of the district's budget, he said. `` If chaos continues, more students will leave and it will be lights out,'' <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> also said some poor families wo n't have access to open enrollment because of transportation costs. In <LOCATION> Edina </LOCATION>, where the 6,000-pupil district is 96 percent white and the average price of a home in 1985 was $ 141,000, the school board voted to opt out of the program. `` We kind of anticipated that this would be viewed as a racially motivated decision,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Edina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> Superintendent <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Smyth </PERSON>, who denied `` elitism'' played a role in the decision. He said open enrollment allows students to transfer schools for athletic purposes and other reasons he considers `` trivial.'' Another drawback is the inevitable erosion of education quality for students who remain in schools of declining enrollment, he said. But <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Edina </LOCATION> wants to `` pick and choose'' its students. `` The law says you ca n't deny a student because of their race or their academic ability or whether they're a problem student. You ca n't select and choose which kids are educated and <LOCATION> Edina </LOCATION> says ` We want to pick and choose,''' she said. The <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teacher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has warmly endorsed open enrollment partly because `` parent and student satisfaction with their school is absolutely vital to their success,'' said <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Zohn </PERSON>, president. But <PERSON> Zohn </PERSON> noted that the <ORGANIZATION> PTA </ORGANIZATION> unsuccessfully lobbied for a declining enrollment fund that would have sent state money for one or two years to schools losing students to give them a chance to improve. <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> joked that the success of schools under open enrollment may someday be linked to their marketing ability. `` How about, ` Come here. We'll give all A's,' or ` Finish four years in three.'''
