<HEAD>Mississippi Governor Wages Emotional Fight To Close Charity Hospitals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> has gotten himself into an emotional battle by proposing to close the three charity hospitals that the nation's poorest state operates for its poorest people. <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> says the poor would be better served if the money that funds the hospitals went instead into Medicaid and attracted federal funds, but opponents claim to have more than 100,000 petition signatures to keep the hospitals open. <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON>, who took office a year ago after a reform-based campaign, says the hospitals are underfunded and represent the lower tier of a double standard of health care in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. `` We have to work toward the day when where you live and how much you make are not the deciding factors in the standard of care you get,'' the 40-year-old Democrat said recently. But he has been unable to convince some people that the health care needs of the poor could be better served by closing <ORGANIZATION> Matty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hersee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Meridian </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Laurel </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Kuhn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vicksburg </LOCATION>. The hospitals, set up in 1916, collectively maintain only 199 of the state's more than 15,800 hospital beds on a budget of $ 6.8 million. They served 77,508 patients in the 1988 fiscal year, out of a population of about 2.5 million. That includes 8,278 who required hospitalization and 69,230 outpatients. `` The buildings are older buildings, but they are well kept and they're very clean,'' said <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Sprayberry </PERSON> of the state <ORGANIZATION> Eleemosynary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees charity hospitals. The governor's plan sparked a recent rally at the state Capitol. `` I do n't have no insurance, no Medicaid and you ca n't get no doctor to wait on you if you do n't have no money,'' said <PERSON> Georgia </PERSON> <PERSON> Mae </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, one of about 300 people who traveled the 90 miles from Laurel for the rally. `` When you go to the state hospital they take good care of you. They do n't ask you if you got money. They just wait on you,'' <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> said. `` If you go to these other hospitals, they're going to turn you out. They're going to say you got to get some money and that's something these people ai n't got. <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> hastily called a news conference to counter the public attention drawn to the rally. `` I think that the people marching today and I have the same aims and that's quality health care for Mississippians,'' <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> said. `` I think as governor I've got to make the decision of how we can get the most health care for the most people.'' <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> has said that putting into Medicaid the money that now goes for the charity hospitals would attract to the state an additional $ 28 million in federal matching dollars. He also has proposed other Medicaid expansions. <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> spent $ 440,258,967 on Medicaid in the 1988 fiscal year, which ended June 30, 1988. Of that, $ 346,324,369 was in federal matching funds and $ 93,934,598 in state funds. <PERSON> Mabus </PERSON> said his plan would provide medical assistance to far more people than are served by the charity hospitals. `` By shifting these funds to Medicaid, we can cover literally tens of thousands more Mississipians statewide. We can do it in a more equitable manner,'' he said. But opponents say they have more than 100,000 signatures on petitions and most legislators from the areas where the hospitals are located have worked against the governor's plan. `` My question is, if you close the charity hospitals, how many working poor people are going to fall through the cracks?'' asked state Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Heflin </PERSON>, whose district includes <PERSON> Matty </PERSON> <PERSON> Hersee </PERSON>. But lawmakers who back the goveror's proposal agree with him that the issue is one of quality health care for the poor. `` I think the people of <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> can be served by the charity hospitals it they're properly funded, but they're not properly funded and the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> has refused to properly fund them for the last 10 years,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Buelow </PERSON>.
