<HEAD>With PM-Steinberg, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Hedda </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> has become a powerful symbol of family violence and could become a powerful advocate for other battered women, says the psychiatrist who is nurturing her recovery. Tragedy put Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> into her role, portrayed by prosecutors as a brainwashed victim of brutality and by <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s defense as a fraud who killed the little girl they illegally adopted and raised until her death at age 6. The once-pretty woman bared her scarred face and psyche to television viewers during testimony that unraveled an all-too-common story of domestic violence. A state jury Monday convicted <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> of manslaughter. When Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>, a 46-year-old former children's book editor for <ORGANIZATION> Random </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, was arrested with <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> after little <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s death, she had a black eye, broken nose, nine fractured ribs, split lip, cauliflower ear, and a leg so severely ulcerated that doctors called the injury life-threatening. Charges against her were dropped when prosecutors determined she was too physically and mentally incapacitated to be responsible for the girl's death. Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> agreed to become the key prosecution witness. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, 47, was charged with beating <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> on the night of Nov. 1, 1987. The death, three days later, of a child from an affluent, well-educated household, shocked many and became a nationwide symbol of family violence as a problem that cuts across social strata. Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>'s testimony described a 12-year relationship in which she was beaten, brainwashed and subjected to other bizarre punishments for transgressions imagined by <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>. Slowly, deliberately, Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> told how she came to see <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> as a `` godlike figure'' _ asking his permission to eat, obeying his orders to sleep on the floor or sit in a tub of cold water. Jurors saw handwritten pages in which Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> vowed to care about <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>'s hair, clothes, work, problems, diet, future, teeth and other concerns. In another paper, she wrote 10 times that `` anger is destructive'' and that `` self-defense is regressive.'' Her psychiatrist, <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Klagsbrun </PERSON>, has said Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> wo n't be ready to leave the Four Winds hospital in <LOCATION> Katonah </LOCATION>, north of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, for at least two months But while she has n't made definite plans, <PERSON> Klagsbrun </PERSON> said he would n't be surprised to see Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> become an advocate for other battered women. `` She feels an obligation at this point to be helpful to others _ in helping people stand up and fight for themselves and regain a level of self-respect,'' said <PERSON> Klagsbrun </PERSON>. `` She's very conscious of the responsibility she now has to take a horrible part of her life and make it useful for other women as well as for herself, her own healing.'' `` She's articulate and intelligent. She has the capacity to relate and be available to other people'' _ and already has helped other patients during her hospitalization, said <PERSON> Klagsbrun </PERSON>. `` Her impact on other people who have experienced battering has been enormous,'' he said. `` She has allowed some people to reveal more than they were prepared to do ... to feel they can assert themselves in society and stand up to evil. People have said things along those lines to her.'' During seven days of testimony in December, Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> told her in bed, after they had free-based cocaine and while <PERSON> Li