<SECOND>PM-Bus Drivers-Manners,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Urban Bus Company Sends Drivers To Charm School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DINA KYRIAKIDOU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> ATHENS </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> _ In a bid to control hot Mediterranean tempers and teach them a smattering of English for the benefit of tourists, <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> bus drivers are being sent to charm school. The $ 4.3 million program is aimed at improving the image of the capital's public transportation system, which faces stiff competition from taxis whose cost is among the cheapest in the world. Classes such as `` Driver and Communication with the Public'' and `` English for Drivers'' are part of the 15-day courses for the staff of the semi-private <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>. `` The classes will help the driver control his Mediterranean temperament ... but passengers must also understand that it's not the driver's fault when the bus is late,'' said <PERSON> Andreas </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolas </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Union of Bus Drivers. Quarrels often break out between bus drivers and passengers irked by waiting for buses or when riders insist on getting off where there is no bus stop. Because of the chaotic state of public transportation _ bus routes and timetables are rarely available _ tourists often take taxis, which cost about $ 2 for a three-mile ride. The bus fare is 20 cents. <PERSON> Kolas </PERSON> said drivers' manners are n't helped by the aggravation of navigating the capital's notoriously congested streets. According to the transit company's chairman, <PERSON> Vassilis </PERSON> <PERSON> Xeomeritis </PERSON>, about 3,500 of the 5,000 bus drivers are very experienced but `` older people with almost no education. `` Our drivers could use some retraining ... they must understand that passengers are our customers and that it's the driver's duty to serve the public,'' <PERSON> Xenomeritis </PERSON> said. The corporation's 1,200 buses cover the whole of <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> _ a 120-square-mile area. With only one subway line crossing the city, more than 70 percent of Athenians commute by bus daily. A bus driver who would n't let his name be used said the public should also `` learn how to behave'' and use the transportation system properly. `` Passengers sometimes ask us unbelievable things,'' he said. `` We try to explain something to them and they are already so upset that they turn around and swear at us.'' About 1,500 drivers are scheduled for the course in 1989. The rest will take it in the next couple of years, said <PERSON> Christos </PERSON> <PERSON> Halazias </PERSON>, a transportation company spokesman. The corporation received almost half its financial backing for the training program from the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, he said.
