<FIRST>r w PM-FarmingHeresy Bjt   01-31 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farming Heresy, Bjt,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Plow That Broke the Plain Is Under Lock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> farmer <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> Berntson </PERSON> stood before an audience at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> and spoke what he admitted sounded like heresy: Lock the plow in the barn, he advised, and farm without tilling. `` My neighbors say it is sacrilege, unpatriotic and everything else,'' he said. `` It was the plow that opened the prairie. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> made improvements to the plow. Why, the plow is mentioned in the Bible.'' Yet what <PERSON> Berntson </PERSON> advocated was n't heresy here. He was a participant in a <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> conference Monday on a new breeze in farming _ low-input agriculture. That's maximum farming with minimal disturbance to nature, farming with seed, soil and manure and as little chemistry as possible. The movement is similar in some respects to `` organic'' farming, although many low-input practitioners find they ca n't stay in business without using herbicides and other chemicals scorned by their more dogmatic counterparts. With drought blowing the topsoil away, the cost of petrochemicals skyrocketing and farmers coming under the scrutiny of the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> for polluting groundwater, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> decided to take a fresh look at low-impact farming. Keynoter <PERSON> Will </PERSON> <PERSON> Erwin </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> farmer, said public impatience has given urgency to the cause. He summed up the public's attitude toward farmers this way: `` We paid you not to produce so much and you used chemicals and fertilizers to produce more, and spoiled the environment to boot.'' With his topsoil only six inches deep and more blowing away every time he plowed, <PERSON> Berntson </PERSON>, a third generation wheat farmer in northeastern <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, started no-tillage farming 10 years ago, raising wheat and barley from acres that normally get a mere 18 inches of rain a year. Does it pay off? The jury is out, he said. Farming his way is costly and still requires a lot of herbicides to control weeds, doing what his locked-up plow once did. He puts so much stuff on the weeds, he said, that `` we say we are plowing with a can and a jug.'' As for his neighbors, `` They are not quite ready to go to no-till, and maybe they're smarter than I am.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spends just $ 3.9 million of its $ 25 billion annual budget on `` alternative agriculture.'' <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, a west-central <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> farmer, pleaded with it to do more. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, who raises corn and soybeans with three sons on 3,300 acres, said he, too, has parked his plow, `` and if this makes me a good guy, I guess I qualify.'' He's a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, but he can hardly be called a low-input farmer, he said. To get corn yields of 150 to 200 bushels per acre, this is what he pours onto each acre: $ 24 in seeds, $ 51 in fertilizer, $ 18 in herbicides, $ 12 in insecticides and $ 50 to $ 60 worth of electricity to run the irrigation system. `` We know this is wrong,'' said <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, `` but we do n't know what else to do about it because we still have to make a living. I belong to a lot of organizations that recognize the problem. But I have to make a living.''
</TEXT>
