<HEAD>VA Employees Disciplined for Being too Cozy with Drug Companies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thirty-two medical employees of the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> have been disciplined for accepting money and other gratuities from drug companies doing business with the agency. The <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that its department of medicine and surgery took the action as a result of a three-year investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> inspector general into dealings between <LOCATION> VA </LOCATION> doctors and other employees and five pharmaceutical suppliers. The actions were for the acceptance of travel expenses, speaking fees, grants or consulting fees, and for being absent from work without taking vacation to do the outside work, the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> said. The probe began after an earlier investigation into dealings by another drug company resulted in disciplinary actions against 34 <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> physicians and other employees in 1987. In response to a Freedom of Information Act request, the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION>'s office of inspector general said that in the latest actions one employee was suspended, 29 received admonishments and two received reprimands, which are more serious than admonishments In three other cases no action was taken because the employees resigned. Six cases were referred to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which decided against prosecution in four of them, in most cases citing lack of criminal intent. The other two cases remain under consideration. In addition, the agency provided counseling to 18 employees and issued instructional letters to 473 employees _ steps that were the result of the investigation but are not considered disciplinary actions. The inspector general withheld names of the employees involved. In a written statement, the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> said the employees violated regulations or policies concerning actual or apparent conflict of interest through the improper acceptance of money or other gratuities. Many of the cases involved <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> doctors or other employees attending or speaking at meetings and symposiums sponsored by the companies. Assistant Inspector General <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kroll </PERSON> said the investigation has not been closed and that actions involving several <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> employees have not been completed. Investigative reports released by the inspector general said that in one case, a VA doctor employed part-time received fees and expenses totaling over $ 175,000 from <ORGANIZATION> Eli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and for two years had a $ 10,000 a year consulting agreement with <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON>. During that period he served as chairman of a VA hospital's formulary committee, a panel that selects drugs for use by the hospital In another case, a <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> employee received speeking fees amounting to $ 35,050 and expenses of $ 14,018, and was absent from work for 335 hours, the agency said. In still another, an employee received honoraria from two companies on 79 occasions, including fees of $ 38,250 and expenses of $ 34,018. In addition to <ORGANIZATION> Lilly </ORGANIZATION>, companies involved were <ORGANIZATION> Ciba-Geigy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Hoechst-Roussel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceuticals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Merk-Sharp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Dome, and <ORGANIZATION> Abbott </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>. The original investigation involved payments by <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATIO