<FIRST>r w PM-S&amp;Ls-Bush     01-31 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls-Bush,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush's 1984 Report Took Middle Road on S&amp;Ls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is n't talking yet about his plan to restructure the savings and loan system, but the report of a study group he headed as vice president may preview his approach. If the 1984 recommendations of the <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> are any indication, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will take a cautious approach rather than advocate a wholesale restructuring of the industry. The 1984 report recommended maintaining a separate system for S & amp; Ls, at least in the near term, but allowing S & amp; Ls to become banks as their activities and services grew more bank-like. And, rather than calling for a return to old restrictions, the group emphasized a system of incentives _ including risk-based insurance premiums and higher capital levels _ to encourage <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls to operate safely. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s staff director for the task group, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, joined the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> staff last week and is expected to play the key role in shaping the administration's <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L plan. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said Monday that the president hopes to outline the plan in a Feb. 9 speech, although he may not have all the details by then. Much has changed since <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> signed the task group report. But, although the magnitude of S & amp; L insolvencies had not yet come to light, the study recognized what since has been identified as a key contributor to the problem: permissive laws in some states that allowed <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls to stray into risky areas far removed from their traditional business of making home mortgage loans. Rather than force S & amp; Ls to revert to their traditional form, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> group recommended risk-related insurance premiums, requiring institutions entering new areas to pay more into the government insurance fund than conservatively run S & amp; Ls. Currently all S & amp; Ls pay the same premium. Higher levels of capital also would discourage excessive risks, it said. The owner of an S & amp; L with low capital levels has little to lose and much to gain from taking a big risk, while the taxpayers who are the ultimate backers of insured deposits have much to lose and nothing to gain. The task force recommended that S & amp; L capital levels be brought up to the stricter standards applied to commercial banks. That is now being done, but wo n't be in full force until 1991. Contrary to the current thinking of most analysts, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s group advocated that federal regulators turn over some of their authority to the states _ but only to states whose regulatory systems met federal requirements. That would create an incentive for states to develop stronger regulatory programs, it argued. As a guard against states whose standards slip, it said federal insurers should be permitted to revoke the insurance of state-regulated institutions. Currently, there are two schools of thought regarding the future of the S & amp; L industry. One, advocated by the chief industry lobby group, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION>, contends that thrifts should remain distinct from commercial banks, but that they ought to stick primarily to mortgage lending. The other school says there's no longer a need for a separate industry. It notes that commercial banks and mortgage firms owned by non-financial companies such as <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> have entered home mortgages in a big way thanks to government-chartered agencies which buy mortgages and repackage them into securities for sale to investors. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> task force steered a middle course. It recommended retaining the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> for thrifts and keeping three separate insurance funds: for banks, thrifts and credit unions. But it offered a mechanism for the financial system to evolve. Thrifts that stuck primarily to mortgage lending would remain part of a separate system. At a certain point, <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls that entered enough new areas, becoming more like banks, would have to join the bank regulatory system with its stricter regulation.
</TEXT>
