<HEAD>Loophole in Election Law Moves Toward Closing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are moving to close a custom-made loophole in federal election laws allowing some of them to keep unspent campaign funds, a potential personal bonus of up to $ 1 million each. The loophole, which was written to help ensure passage of the 1980 election law, has since lost some of its popularity in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Repealing the provision is now part of a package of legislation related to a pending 50 percent pay raise. `` It's an embarrassment to them,'' <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Ornstein </PERSON>, a political analyst with the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said Monday. `` It's the sort of question not too many members who were there before 1980 want to have asked of them `` I think it's a foregone conclusion that they'll do away with it.'' More than $ 61 million in surplus campaign funds is sitting in the accounts of 191 <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members and 71 senators who were in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> when the law was passed. A `` grandfather clause'' in the law allows them to convert the money for personal use, an action forbidden for those who came to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> later. On the average, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members who were grandfathered in hold about $ 224,000 in their campaign accounts, while senators, whose campaigns usually are considerably more costly, have an average of $ 341,000, according to <ORGANIZATION> FEC </ORGANIZATION> records. `` I did n't go out and spend all the money because that's not the way I operate my own home,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, R-Ky. `` I spend what I think is appropriate to win. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, who cruised to re-election on a 3-to-1 margin last year, had $ 604,824 left over in his campaign account, according to records at the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. That puts him in 10th place among members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. The top spot in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> belongs to Rep. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, with more than $ 1.1 million. <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON> is co-sponsor of a bill that would abolish the grandfather clause. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman, Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., has more than $ 1 million _ up from $ 596,000 since January 1987 _ and has not expressed an opinion on the issue of abolishing the loophole, according to an aide In the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, the list is topped by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, with nearly $ 2.1 million and <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, with $ 1.9 million. However, those amounts are not unusually big war chests since both those senators face re-election campaigns next year. The legislation now before each house would eliminate the possibility of letting the grandfathered members convert leftover funds to their own uses but would continue permitting conversion for the other uses allowed under the law. Candidates for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> can use leftover campaign money to support political organizations or other candidates. In addition, members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> can use the money to `` defray any ordinary and necessary expenses'' arising because of their position. And, unlike the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has a rule forbidding its members from converting their campaign money for personal use, although it does not have the force of law and its effect on former senators or their survivors is unclear. Proposals to abolish the exemption in both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> have come up as members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are about to pick up 50 percent pay raises, boosting salaries from $ 89,500 to $ 135,000 annually for rank-and-file lawmakers. <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> said Monday that he kept his campaign treasury stocked with cash because he represents a largely <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> district and he does n't want to borrow. `` You will never see <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> holding one of these dumb fish frys at $ 25 a head to retire a campaign debt,'' he said. He offered to give back money over the next month to `` anybody who donated to my campaign last time and is not satisfied. Please contact me, and I will send the money back.''
