<HEAD>Former Sheriff Threatens Suit Against ``Mississippi Burning'' Producers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON HARRIST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Rainey </PERSON>, the sheriff when three civil rights workers were slain in rural <LOCATION> Neshoba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> in 1964, is demanding a retraction from the producers of `` Mississippi Burning.'' `` They did n't use my name but nobody in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> or any other state has any doubt they intended that sheriff to be me,'' said <PERSON> Rainey </PERSON>, 65, now employed as a security officer in <LOCATION> Meridian </LOCATION>. `` We will be mailing a demand letter for a retraction on Tuesday and that's a prerequisite for a lawsuit under <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> law,'' said his attorney, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McIntyre </PERSON>. <PERSON> Rainey </PERSON> was acquitted on charges of violating the civil rights of the three workers in a federal trial at which he was represented by <PERSON> McIntyre </PERSON>. <PERSON> McIntyre </PERSON> said the film `` mixes fact with fiction and depicts <PERSON> Rainey </PERSON> as terrorizing citizens of <LOCATION> Neshoba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. It depicts him as being a person bent on violence and it is not an accurate, fair account of what did happen in <LOCATION> Neshoba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> in 1964.'' On June 21, 1964, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaney </PERSON>, 21, who was black, and whites <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, 20 and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwerner </PERSON>, 24, disappeared after they were released from the county jail in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. They had been stopped for speeding after investigating a church burning by the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION>. Their bodies were found 44 days later in a soggy earthen dam in rural <LOCATION> Neshoba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. All three had been shot to death. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>'s `` Mississippi Burning,'' an <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> release, is loosely based on the murders. The film, which stars <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Hackman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Willem </PERSON> <PERSON> Dafoe </PERSON>, has drawn both praise from movie critics and criticism from blacks who contend it gives the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> too much credit in the civil rights struggle. <PERSON> Rainey </PERSON> maintains his innocence and said the movie had subjected him to ridicule. `` The character in the movie was a big man like me and he chewed tobacco like I chewed tobacco all the time,'' said <PERSON> Rainey </PERSON>, who works for a black-owned security firm. `` Everybody knows it was made off the happenings in <LOCATION> Neshoba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>,'' he said Monday. `` The actor had twice as big a crew of tobacco as I ever had but they might have well as called him <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Rainey </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Rainey </PERSON>, who served as <LOCATION> Neshoba </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff from 1964 to 1968, said he had lost a security job in 1975 following a movie based on the civil rights violence in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>. `` I've got a good relationship with blacks,'' he said. `` I'm working for a black man and a black company but he is getting a lot of feedback for working me. The former sheriff said he wanted <PERSON> McIntyre </PERSON> to proceed with a damage suit immediately because `` of the way it has hurt me and is going to hurt me.'' `` If they say ` We are sorry for what has happened and it is n't true,''' <PERSON> McIntyre </PERSON> said, `` that still does not negate a cause of action, it only mitigates the damages. <PERSON> McIntyre </PERSON> noted that of the 18 individuals brought to trial on charges of conspiring to violate the victim's civil rights, only <PERSON> Rainey </PERSON> and a few others were found innocent. Seven were convicted and given sentences ranging from three to 10 years. Calls to <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> were not answered late Monday afternoon.
