<HEAD>Quayle Echoes Early Reagan in Criticism of Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> told religious broadcasters that `` the gospel'' of <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> still pervades the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must be realistic in dealing with that communist nation. Speaking Monday to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Religious </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> had over the years gained an `` appalling confidence in its own wisdom, indeed, its own omniscience.'' `` I think the root of the matter all comes back to a hatred of God, to a rejection of the entire concept of a religious system,'' he said. Comparing the American revolution with the communist revolution in <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said, `` Look how much good has come into the world as a result of the first revolution and how much evil has entered the world because of the second.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is addressing the group Wednesday. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s comments, somewhat reminiscent of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s rhetoric in the early days of his presidency when he called the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> an `` evil empire,'' differed in tone from recent <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> remarks concerning the Soviets <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has used less harsh wording, but has urged a cautious approach to U.S.-Soviet relations, which were improving as <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s term came to an end White House press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s comments were not inconsistent with administration policy <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> quoted <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>, the leader of the 1917 Communist Revolution, as saying the idea of God is `` unutterable vileness ... of the most dangerous kind.'' `` That was <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> and unfortunately his gospel is still actively pursued in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. On the other hand, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> founding fathers had a `` belief in the existence of a Creator whose laws have placed irrevocable limits on the power of the state.'' He also said that if <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s planned 1991 international human rights conference occurs, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must ensure that it `` is not just a public relations extravaganza for the Soviet leadership.'' President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said he would follow through on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s plan for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> participation in the conference, but also has said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials will be watching Soviet human rights performance in the interim. Talking about his trip this week to <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said, `` My message will be democracy, democracy and more democracy,'' he said. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> is not expected to make any policy initiatives during the trip but plans to meet with a number of heads of state who will attend Thursday's inauguration of <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>'s new president, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>.
