<FIRST>r w PM-NursingHomes     01-31 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nursing Homes,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Regulations Aim at Protecting Patients' Rights, Improving Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's 15,000 nursing homes will have to meet higher standards of care and give patients more say in their treatment, under new regulations for Medicaid and Medicare reimbursement. The final regulations, announced Monday, cap several years of efforts by the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to meet the terms of a law passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1987 to improve the quality of nursing home care. `` These regulations change our focus in regulating nursing homes, away from looking to see merely if a facility has the capacity to deliver care, to looking at the quality of care that is actually being delivered,'' said Dr. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roper </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> HCFA </ORGANIZATION> administrator. Among other things, the regulations will: _ Give patients the right to refuse treatment, manage their own money, receive visitors, manage their own privacy, express grievances, be free of physical restraints and not be transferred or discharged against their will _ Offer patients services needed to treat specific conditions and guard against such things as inappropriate weight gain and loss and bed sores _ Require nursing homes to have 24-hour nursing capability, including a registered nurse for eight hours of every day _ Require facilities to train nurses' aides, provide dental, vision and hearing care, and offer an activities program by a qualified professional The final regulations will apply to nearly 15,000 long-term care facilities. The rules are open to a 90-day comment period and most will go into effect 90 days after that. The rest will go into effect Oct. 1, 1990. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents licensed nursing homes and long-term health care facilities, generally endorsed the regulations, but expressed concern about the length of time it is taking to put them in place. The group also is concerned that `` if there is not adequate funding for them, they wo n't have the impact they were intended to have,'' said <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Keegan </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the association. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nursing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said it was `` extremely concerned at the disregard for the quality of care'' in the regulations. <PERSON> Lucille </PERSON> <PERSON> Joel </PERSON>, president of the nursing association, criticized the rules for permitting <ORGANIZATION> HFCA </ORGANIZATION> to waive a requirement that a registered nurse be on duty for eight hours a day, seven days a week. The <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> agency has proposed no criteria on which to grant waivers `` and has implied that the waivers may be used as a way to cut the budget for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> and Medicaid nursing home programs,'' she said. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyer </PERSON>, director of provider service coverage policy at HFCA, said the law allows waivers only when a nursing home ca n't find nurses to hire and would be granted only if quality of care were not affected. The agency will be issuing proposed rules for waiver requirements in the next couple of months, he said.
