<FIRST>r w PM-ProstateCancer     01-31 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prostate Cancer,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Approves Combined Drug, Hormone Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new drug therapy can extend the lives of men with advanced prostate cancer by nearly 25 percent, according to a study on which the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> based its approval of the new treatment. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> on Monday approved the new hormone-blocking drug flutamide for use in combination with another drug that affects hormone production in patients whose prostate cancers are in the most advanced stage. The drug will be marketed under the trade name Eulexin by the <ORGANIZATION> Schering-Plough </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> cautioned that `` flutamide is not a cure,'' but he said a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> study `` demonstrated how it can be used to extend the lives of some men.'' Young also stressed that when detected in the early stages, prostate cancer can be treated successfully. `` These prostate cancers generally need not get to this stage _ if every man over 40 would have a simple rectal exam each year,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. Cancer of the prostate, a walnut-size gland at the base of the male bladder, is the third leading cause of cancer deaths among American men. It kills more than 25,000 men annually and about 100,000 new cases are reported each year, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. The disease often develops with no noticeable symptoms. Warning signs can include difficulty in urinating, frequent urination and presence of blood or pus in the urine or semen. These are the same symptoms that mark prostate infections and a benign enlargement of the prostate that is common in older men. In its early stages, the disease can be treated successfully by removing all or part of the prostate or by radiation. But if the cancer spreads to other tissue and organs, chances of successful treatment diminish considerably. The <ORGANIZATION> NCI </ORGANIZATION> study involving 617 men with advanced prostate cancer showed that flutamide, in combination with the previously approved drug leuprolide, extended survival by nearly 25 percent. Patients receiving the two drugs survived an average 34.9 months, seven months longer than the group that received leuprolide alone, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. The drug has been in clinical development for 15 years and is marketed in 34 countries, <ORGANIZATION> Schering-Plough </ORGANIZATION> said. The drug works by blocking the spread of cancer cells in the prostate as well as in surrounding tissue. Scientists believe the male hormone testosterone stimulates proliferation of cancer cells by a diseased prostate. Leuprolide stops production of the hormone by the testes, and flutamide is believed to inhibit the hormone's action on cancer cells by blocking the receptor sites that testosterone uses in the cells, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said. Side effects of the combined therapy included hot flashes in 61 percent of the patients, loss of libido in 36 percent, impotence in 33 percent, diarrhea in 14 percent and nausea and vomiting in 12 percent, the agency said.
</TEXT>
