 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is being asked to rethink its decision to require bridges to be inspected every four years instead of every two years, as previously required. An auto safety advocacy group and relatives of people killed in a 1987 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> bridge collapse said in a petition filed Monday, `` FHwA failed to obtain crucial information relevant to the decision and consequently could not make a knowledgeable analysis of the effects of less frequent bridge inspections.'' The new rule was passed in August and affects about 122,000 bridges nationwide. The federal agency `` has issued the final rule despite the documented inadequacies of state bridge inspection programs covering 576,000 bridges,'' <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ditlow </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, executive director of the Center for Auto Safety, said in a letter accompanying the petition that asks the agency to review the rule change. Also filing the petition were relatives of three people who were among 10 killed when the <LOCATION> Schoharie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> bridge on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thruway </ORGANIZATION> fell into the <LOCATION> Schoharie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> on April 5, 1987, after days of rain and flooding.
