<NOTE>Study Says Electric Power Shortages Possible in 1990s</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> power companies must build more generating capacity than currently planned or the nation may face an electricity shortage in the 1990s, a trade group says. Based on conservative projections of growth in electricity demand, the nation will need an additional 50,000 megawatts of generating capacity by 1997 in order to avoid a shortage, a newly published <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> study said Monday. That amount would be needed in addition to the 32,500 megawatts of capacity currently under construction, the study said. Using an assumption of faster electricity demand growth over the next decade, which the gas group said it considered to be more realistic, an additional 105,000 megawatts of plant capacity would be needed to avoid shortages. The study said 71 percent of capacity additions planned in the 1979-88 period were canceled.
