<TEXT>
 Sellers
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Handgun manufacturers and sellers would be liable for injuries and deaths caused by the weapons, under a new proposal by the <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. The proposal `` is designed to force gun manufacturers to consider carefully the purposes for which handguns are manufactured,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Clarke </PERSON>, the bill's sponsor. Sponsors of the legislation said it will be the first of its kind in the nation. The plan would hold handgun manufacturers, importers and dealers liable for damage caused by handguns, in the same manner that some states hold tavern owners or party hosts liable for injuries caused by drunken drivers. The bill is supported by 12 of the 13 council members in a city whose officials are worried about a rising murder rate. January is already the bloodiest month in city history, with 49 killings through Monday. The highest yearly total was set in 1988 when 372 people were killed in the nation's capital.
