<HEAD>Raw Materials Prices Reached Top Levels in 1988</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, bgng: ``It calculated...'' to drop extra
word `dollars'; INSERTS 1 graf after 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``In addition...''
to add oil prices; picks up 8th graf pvs, bgng: ``Penelope Hartland-Thunberg...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prices for raw materials all over the world reached their highest level for the 1980s last year, according to figures collected by the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. It calculated that the drought in this country pushed the average price of wheat to $ 168.90 a metric ton, or $ 4.69 a bushel, last month, compared with an average of $ 112.10 a metric ton, or $ 3.11 a bushel, in 1987. Big demand by the industrial countries of east <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> helped raise the price of copper to a record $ 3,498.90 a metric ton, nearly $ 1.20 a pound, the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The average rise for a long list of commodities was 10.2 percent for the year. That brought the overall level to just a little _ 2.8 percent _ above the average for the years 1979 to 1981. Problems of Third World countries have been aggravated in recent years by low prices they have been getting for the products of fields and mines, their chief source of foreign income. For some, things are now improving. Aluminum, nickel, rice, sugar, bananas, fats and oils were all up for the year. Timber, cotton and oranges were down. In addition to the Arab countries of the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, oil is a major export for <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> and others. <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION> benefits doubly: from the rise in the copper price and the drop in the oil price, because oil is a big import. The average oil price in 1988 was $ 13.60 a barrel compared with $ 17.20 a barrel in 1987, and the price dropped as low as $ 11.60 a barrel in the fourth quarter of 1988. However, oil prices increased steadily in December, reflecting growing market confidence in the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>' November decision to set a production ceiling of 18.5 million barrels a day, according to the report. <PERSON> Penelope </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartland-Thunberg </PERSON>, trade expert at the independent <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strategic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>, said that commodity prices go in short-term cycles, now up and now down. But the long term trend is now toward a decline as new inventions come into use and fewer raw materials are used for each dollar of goods produced. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION>, pointed out that there is sometimes a wide spread even within individual commodities. High quality arabica coffees from the highlands of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION> are being bought more and more in western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, he said. The report credited the reintroduction of export quotas under the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agreement </ORGANIZATION> as helping raise the price of arabicas by 20 percent in 1988. That meant a shift away from the lower grade robusta coffees grown nearer the sea in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>. Their prices were down by 8 percent. <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> also emphasized the uneven effects of price movements. `` The newly industrialized countries in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> are importing feed for pigs and poultry,'' he said. `` That pushes up the price of grain up for the low income countries of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, which have to buy more because they're producing less themselves and there's less foreign aid available.'' <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> countries, especially the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, are suffering from low prices for both their coffee and cocoa.
</TEXT>
