<HEAD>Authorities: Two Arrested in Chemical Weapons Shipments To Iran And
Iraq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VALERIE MEEHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businessman and a Dutch national have been arrested for diverting shipments of an industrial lubricant to <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> for use as a chemical weapon by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, authorities said. Besides announcing the arrests, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities said Monday that a Baltimore-based company agreed to plead guilty to one count of violating export laws in connection with the export of thiodiglycol. The lubricant, used in inks and textiles and sold under the brand name <PERSON> Kromfax </PERSON>, produces lethal mustard gas when combined with hydrochloric acid. <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Defino </PERSON>, 64, of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and Dutch citizen <PERSON> Frans </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Amraat </PERSON>, who was apprehended in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, on Jan. 26, were charged with conspiracy, listing phony destinations on export documents and violating <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> export laws. <PERSON> Defino </PERSON> surrendered to <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> agents in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> on Monday and was released on bond after appearing before a magistrate. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Amraat </PERSON> is awaiting extradition. The chemicals, manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Alcolac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, were illegally shipped to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> by separate agents during 1987 and 1988, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Breckinridge </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Willcox </PERSON>. The two men were accused of shipping the chemical to <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> then to <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>. From there, the chemical was transported to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Willcox </PERSON>. Four shipments, each weighing more than 100 tons, were sent to <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in 1987 and 1988, but at least three wound up in <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, according to the federal complaint. Last year, a West German pleaded guilty to purchasing a component of mustard gas from <ORGANIZATION> Alcolac </ORGANIZATION> and shipping it via <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <PERSON> DeFino </PERSON> conducted business with <ORGANIZATION> Alcolac </ORGANIZATION> through <ORGANIZATION> Nu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, purchasing the more than 400 tons of the chemical, authorities said. <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Amraat </PERSON> was the European agent for Nu <PERSON> Kraft </PERSON>, authorities said. <PERSON> Willcox </PERSON> said <PERSON> Defino </PERSON> is vice president of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Alcolac </ORGANIZATION> officials said the chemicals were sent to the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> without their knowledge. `` That was not my understanding,'' said <PERSON> Willcox </PERSON>, who refused to elaborate. <ORGANIZATION> Alcolac </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> said the company was unaware the chemicals were going to the destinations other than the European points listed on shipping documents. He said the company has cooperated fully with federal investigators. One former employee filled out the shipping documents in a way that ran afoul of the complex provisions of the Export Administration Act, <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> said. The employee did not know the eventual destinations, he said. <PERSON> Willcox </PERSON> declined to say whether the worker would be charged. `` No one within this company had any indication that these materials were going to be diverted to the Iran-Iraq war zone,'' <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> said. `` We feel just awful that one of our products was misused for that end use.'' The federal investigation previously led to the arrest in July of <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Walaschek </PERSON>, a West German employee of <ORGANIZATION> Chemco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> G.m.b.h. </ORGANIZATION>, who purchased three shipments of the chemical during 1987 and 1988 for shipment to <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and then re-exported them to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Willcox </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Walaschek </PERSON> pleaded guilty to violating American export law for arranging the shipments. After initially agreeing to cooperate with prosecutors as an informant, <PERSON> Walaschek </PERSON> fled the country, forfeiting a $ 350,000 bond, authorities said. <PERSON> Willcox </PERSON> said talks were continuing with West German officials about extraditing <PERSON> Walaschek </PERSON>. Chemco had purchased thiodiglycol at the direction of Sexed Kharim <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Sobhani </PERSON>, an Iranian diplomat stationed in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported Sunday. Under American law, exporting the chemical requires a license. Shipments to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> are barred. Chemco purchased three shipments of thiodiglycol from <ORGANIZATION> Alcolac </ORGANIZATION> and 90 tons were delivered to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in 1987 and 1988, <PERSON> Willcox </PERSON> said. A later shipment of 120 tons was intercepted by Customs investigators, who substituted water for the chemical and then traced their travels to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, authorities said. One ton of thiodiglycol produces about a ton of mustard gas. One hundred tons would cover about 50 square miles.
