<HEAD>Solarz Reports Pakistani Offer to Verify No-Weapons Pledge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``Solarz said...'' to add Beg's first
name; SUBS 8th graf pvs, bgng: ``The network...'' to correct location of
plant; picks up 9th graf pvs, bgng: ``Pakistan is...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pakistani officials are willing for the first time to agree to verification that they are not building nuclear weapons if they are permitted to buy U.S.-made reactors for power production, says a senior member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Rep. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who brought the proposal back from a recent trip to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, said Monday it deserves serious consideration and he will hold hearings on the idea in his <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> subcommittee. <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON> said `` key'' Pakistani officials had endorsed the reactors-for-safeguards swap but declined to say which ones. During his stay in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> he met with new Prime Minister <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Ghulam </PERSON> <PERSON> Ishaq </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> and army Chief of Staff Gen. <PERSON> Aslam </PERSON> <PERSON> Beg </PERSON>, among others. Under the proposal, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> would agree to some form of negotiated verification process to ensure that its nuclear program is put only to peaceful uses, and is not devoted to weapons development. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s nuclear intentions have been a source of friction in past relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, although <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy-makers sought to put those concerns aside in recent years because of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s cooperation in funneling weapons to the anti-Soviet rebels in neighboring <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Now that Soviet troops are being withdrawn, however, the nuclear issue has come back to the forefront of relations between the two countries. Administration officials have said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> may be cut off after Sept. 30 because President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will not be unable to certify that the Pakistanis have not developed a nuclear weapon. Further details of the <LOCATION> Pakistani </LOCATION> weapons program were reported Monday by <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, which said nuclear materials made in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> found their way to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> through by way of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The network said heavy water from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> weapons reactor complex near <LOCATION> Aiken </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, was sold to a West German company and was processed 15 to 20 years later into the tritium gas used to build nuclear warheads. Then, after being sold and resold, it reached another <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> firm, <ORGANIZATION> NTG </ORGANIZATION>, which shipped the gas to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> said. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is receiving $ 230 million in military aid and $ 215 million in economic aid from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this year, making it the third largest beneficiary of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid after <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON> said an agreement that would provide safeguards against Pakistani weapons development could not only head off a prickly showdown over <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid, but it also could facilitate a budding reconciliation between <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and neighboring <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. `` If the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is willing to sell nuclear reactors for peaceful nuclear energy, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> would agree to establish full-scope safeguards on all their nuclear facilities, including existing ones,'' <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON> said in describing the proposal made by <LOCATION> Pakistani </LOCATION> officials. `` If we can cap the Pakistani nuclear program at its present level, that would represent a very significant and constructive development.'' <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> in the past has refused to cooperate in international inspection procedures under a non-proliferation treaty. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> said recently that her country will not sign the international treaty unless <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> does too. <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON> noted that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s relatively high level of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid was based on its key role in supporting the Afghan rebels, and that the withdrawal of Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> would lessen the need for military aid. But he said there might be a greater need for economic aid than in the past. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, in its 1991 budget proposal, asked that military aid levels to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> be increased to $ 240 million and economic aid be increased to $ 250 million.
