<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a new offensive against drug traffickers, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s narcotics police destroyed eight cocaine laboratories, 2,310 pounds of cocaine and 44 runways in remote areas, the national police chief said. The raids, all in jungle areas, occurred last weekend as part of Operation Springtime, Gen. <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> said in a news release on Monday. <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> took over the national police last month in one of the frequent changes of command in government security forces. New police commanders frequently come on strong with a series of raids. Eight people, who had all made just a few dollars a day as laborers at the cocaine processing labs, were arrested in the weekend raids, <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> said. Not one of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s dozen major cocaine bosses has ever been arrested on drug trafficking charges and convicted in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. An average of two dozen cocaine processing labs are destroyed in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> each year, and scores of clandestine runways are bombed by the air force. New labs and new runways appear within weeks. A police colonel told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> last year that there probably were more than 500 clandestine runways in use by drug traffickers in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> at any given time. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government gives about $ 15 million worth of aid to <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> each year in the form of equipment and training to fight drug trafficking. Colombian narcotics officials have suggested privately that $ 15 million dollars does not go far toward stopping the multibillion-dollar illegal cocaine trafficking in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. Scores of helicopters and thousands of police would be needed to deal effectively with the problem, the officials have said pri