<FIRST>r a PM-Steinberg-Charges     01-31 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Steinberg-Charges,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>An Explanation of the Charges In the Steinberg Child Abuse Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Steinberg, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, who faced four homicide counts in the death of his 6-year-old illegally adopted daughter, <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON>, was acquitted of the most serious charge and convicted of the second-most serious. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> was charged with second-degree murder, which would have required a finding by the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury that he had recklessly struck the girl and then showed depraved indifference to her life by failing to get medical help. The jury acquitted him of that charge, which carries a sentence of 25 years to life in prison. The charge on which <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> was convicted _ first-degree manslaughter _ required the jury to find that he intended to cause serious physical harm to the girl, and that the injury caused her death. The charge carries a maximum penalty of 8 1 @ 3 to 25 years in prison. The judge had instructed the jury it could infer that <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> intended to cause the injury `` by the results produced by his act.'' But if they found his use of cocaine had so dulled his awareness that he could not form intent, they were to find him innocent of first-degree manslaughter. The jury did not need to consider the two lesser charges: second-degree manslaughter and criminally negligent homicide. The former requires action that is reckless but not with depraved indifference. It carries a five-to-15-year prison sentence. The latter covers situations in which a death is caused by someone who fails to perceive the risk of his actions. It carries a term of 1 1 @ 3 to four years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
