<HEAD>Radicals Attack U.S. Cultural Center _ Yet Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shouting `` Yankee go home,'' dozens of radical students hurled firebombs today at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cultural center in <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said. It was the second such attack this month. About 30 firebombs were thrown, but none landed inside the compound, said an official at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. The official, who requesting anonymity, said there were no injuries or damage. About 50 students shouted anti-U.S. slogans as they dashed out of alleys and hurled dozens of firebombs and rocks toward the center, the <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. Most of the bombs landed on the street, it said. `` Drive out <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION> who manipulated the <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> massacre,'' <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION> quoted students as shouting. They also chanted `` Shut down the <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> center'' and `` Punish -LRB- former President -RRB- <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> <PERSON> Doo-hwan </PERSON> and -LRB- President -RRB- <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> Tae-woo,'' the agency said. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> was elected in December 1987 and replaced <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>, who stepped down after seven years of authoritarian rule and played a leading role in the brutal military suppression of the 1980 <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> uprising. About 100 riot police guarding the center charged at the attackers, firing tear gas, and chased them away in a few minutes, <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION> said. The agency did not say whether any students were arrested. On Jan. 18, about 50 students attacked the center with sledgehammers, rocks and firebombs and broke windows. No one was hurt. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, who say the center has been attacked eight times in the past last year by radical students, today denied reports that they have decided to close it. But they said the facility could close if the attacks continue. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been seeking promises from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> authorities that they will provide adequate protection for the <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> center and its staff. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cultural centers in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pusan </LOCATION> have also been attacked, but not as frequently as the <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> center. The centers have libraries and occassionaly offer speaker programs. Anti-U.S. sentiment is relatively high in <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION>, an opposition stronghold 180 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, because of the suppression of the 1980 pro-democracy civil uprising in the southern city. By official count, about 200 people were killed and more than 1,000 injured or wounded as government troops put down the nine-day armed revolt. Many opposition and dissident figures claim the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was involved in the <LOCATION> Kwangju </LOCATION> incident by supporting a South Korean government plan to quell the uprising ruthlessly. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has denied any involvement in the incident and agreed to submit written testimony from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> lawmakers who are conducting parliamentary investigations into misdeeds committed under <PERSON> Chun </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has 42,000 troops stationed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> under a mutual defense treaty and many radical students want the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers to leave.
