<HEAD>Soviet Missiles Reported to Kill 70 Amid Pullout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Soviet missile attack; UPDATE
with U.S. Embassy staff departing; CLARIFY that diplomats believe attacks
aimed at forcing political settlement; picks up 7th graf pvs `In Washington...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> ISLAMABAD </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> _ Four long-range <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> missiles slammed into villages today near the main Soviet withdrawal route and killed 70 people, Moslem guerrillas said. Western diplomats said an upsurge in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> and government attacks during the past week appeared to be aimed at pressuring the guerrillas to reach a political settlement with the Soviet-backed government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. The diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> is expected to be out of the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> area by Feb. 6. <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> pledged in a U.N.-brokered accord last year to remove all of its more than 100,000 combat troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by Feb. 15. Although the final phase of the pullout is in full swing in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, the diplomats did not predict when the Soviets would leave other parts of the country, notably <LOCATION> Shindand </LOCATION> air base in western <LOCATION> Farah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Province </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Jamiat-i-Islami </ORGANIZATION>, one of the major Afghan guerrilla factions, said it received news of today's missile attack in a radio report from its commander, <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> <PERSON> Masood </PERSON>. The guerrillas said the SS-1 Scud missiles hit in the <LOCATION> Khinja </LOCATION> section of the <LOCATION> Panjshir </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> about 30 miles northeast of the Salang Highway. There was no independent confirmation of the missile attacks. Official Afghan media have accused <PERSON> Masood </PERSON> of attacking convoys carrying food to the capital. However, the Jamiat faction said the convoys also were loaded with arms and ammunition for the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> regime. Combined Soviet and Afghan government forces have leveled villages and killed hundreds of people since Jan. 23 in coordinated high-altitude bombing attacks, artillery barrages, missile launches and ground assaults, according to Western and guerrilla sources. Most of the attacks were targeted along the <LOCATION> Salang </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Highway </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s main pullout route between <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and the Soviet border, they said. But they said villages up to 30 miles away from the road also suffered. Also today, the 11 remaining members of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> staff in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> left the country a day after closing their mission because of concerns about fighting in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> after the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> leaves. The embassy staff flew out of the Afghan capital aboard a chartered plane to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, and they are expected to go to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> later this week. Although the embassy was closed Monday, the Americans could not immediately depart because <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> airport was shut by a three-inch snowfall. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> accused the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> of pursuing what it called a `` scorched earth'' policy as its troops withdraw. By contrast, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said, U.S.-armed Afghan insurgents were showing restraint toward the departing <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. `` The Soviets continue what might even be called a scorched earth policy, as they continue very, very intensive air activity,'' <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said. `` We just do n't believe that this kind of a policy is what is called for at the time when <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> ought to be looking to the future.'' One Western diplomat in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> said `` the Soviet bombing and missile attacks can not be explained by a putative Soviet desire to protect its retreating troops.'' He said the guerrillas `` have not been attacking the withdrawing Soviet troops on the <LOCATION> Salang </LOCATION> or elsewhere.'' `` The situation for survivors of these attacks is bleak,'' said another diplomat. `` Survivors have been left homeless in the midst of one of the worst winters in recent memory, in most cases without provisions.'' The communists seized power in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> in a 1978 coup, touching off a civil war with Moslem insurgents. Soviet forces intervened in December 1979 to replace one pro-Moscow government with another, then remained to fight the guerrillas.
