ed in the warrants is <PERSON> Marco </PERSON> <PERSON> Affatigato </PERSON>, a reputed leader of New Order, an extreme rightist group accused of a string of terrorist attacks in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> in the 1970s and early 1980s. Affatigato is believed to be in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. Among Mafia suspects rounded up in raids were members of the <PERSON> Corleone </PERSON> family, considered <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION>'s most powerful Mafia clan, and of the Minore family from <PERSON> Trapani </PERSON>, a Sicilian port linked to clandestine drug and arms shipments. The man considered the <PERSON> Corleone </PERSON> family's `` cashier,'' <PERSON> Michele </PERSON> <PERSON> Cillari </PERSON>, was among more noted figures arrested on Monday. The judge said the investigation stemmed from the 1987 discovery of arms and drugs aboard a Lebanese ship off <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Adriatic </LOCATION> coast. The ship set out from <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and was loaded with heroin, hashish, an anti-tank bazooka, a Soviet grenade-launcher and other arms. Initially, it was linked to alleged arms smuggling between <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, including clandestine delivery of mines to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Several Italian industrialists and arms manufacturers were arrested but later released and charges dropped. On Monday, official said documents seized in connection with the ship led them to the ring. Evidence included false certificates of a dummy bank called the `` Canadian <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>'' of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>. The gang allegedly plotted to deliver French Mirage jetfighters to <LOCATION> Guinea-Bissau </LOCATION>, acting as middlemen in return for kickbacks, authorities said. The scheme allegedly involved an Italian representative of the African country and an official of the French aircraft company <ORGANIZATION> Dassault-Breguet </ORGANIZATION>. It was not known if the planes were delivered.
