<BYLINE>By JOHN MOSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEAVER CREEK, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Cadiz </LOCATION>, who died after skiing into a cable at the World Alpine Ski Championships, was remembered as someone who liked to `` ski fast and drive fast.'' <PERSON> Alfonso </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON> <PERSON> y </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Dampierre </PERSON>, a 52-year-old first cousin of King <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> and member of the international governing body of ski racing, had been skiing Monday with companions when he collided with the cable, which was being raised to support a banner at the finish line of a course at Beaver Creek Resort, officials said. No official cause of death has been determined, but he suffered severe neck lacerations, said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Beavers </PERSON> of the Eagle County Sheriff's Department. King <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> and Queen <LOCATION> Sofia </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> expressed their sorrow over his death. The victim's brother, <PERSON> Gonzalo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON>, said he would fly from <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> today to bring his body back to <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> for burial. The accident occurred Monday afternoon as the slalom course was being converted for downhill competition. Members of the ski patrol and emergency personnel attended to the duke at the scene, but he was pronounced dead on arrival at <ORGANIZATION> Vail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Beavers </ORGANIZATION> said. Beavers said authorities were continuing to interview witnesses. All Monday night events were canceled by World Championship officials, who ordered flags flown at half-staff and made plans for a memorial service. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON>, who was not in the line of succession to the <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> throne, had served as <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s ambassador to <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> from 1969 to 1973. An avid skier, he was president of the Spanish Skiing Federation from 1977 to 1984 and president of the Spanish Olympic Committee from 1984 to 1987. He was a member of the Council of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ski </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>. `` This is a very sad occasion,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Knous </PERSON>, head of the <LOCATION> Vail-Beaver </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> World Championship Organizing Committee. `` This was something none of us ever hoped to see anywhere, especially at an event of this magnitude.'' <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON>'s father was the elder brother of King <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON>' father Both men's fathers were the sons of King <PERSON> Alfonso </PERSON> <PERSON> XIII </PERSON>, who abdicated the Spanish throne in 1931. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON> was a descendant of <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> XIV </PERSON>, the French <PERSON> Sun </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, and was the Bourbon or `` legitimist'' candidate for king had the monarchy ever been restored in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. In 1972, he married <PERSON> Carmen </PERSON> <PERSON> Franco </PERSON>, granddaughter of the late Spanish dictator <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Franco </PERSON>, but they divorced in 1982. In February 1984, he again made headlines following an auto accident in which the older of his two sons was killed on the way home from a skiing trip in the Spanish Basque country. A judge ruled that <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON>, who was driving, had been negligent and stripped him of the custody of his other son. <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez-Ochoa </PERSON>, the slalom gold medalist at the 1972 Olympics and a close friend of the duke, said <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Borbon </PERSON> liked to `` ski fast and drive fast.'' Referring to the duke's divorce, the fatal auto accident and the skiing tragedy, <PERSON> Fernandez-Ochoa </PERSON> described the victim as `` an unlucky person. Bad things happened to him.'' It was the second tragedy involving a ski official during a major event in the past year. In the 1988 Winter Olympics at <LOCATION> Calgary </LOCATION>, Dr. <PERSON> Joerg </PERSON> <PERSON> Oberhammer </PERSON>, a prominent Austrian surgeon affiliated with that country's ski team, was killed when he was knocked into the path of a snow-grooming machine.
