<HEAD>Man Freed After 30 Years on Death Row</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A court today acquitted a man who spent 30 years on death row for the kidnap and murder of a 6-year-old girl. It was <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s fourth case in six years in which a death row inmate was acquitted of murder in a retrial. In all four cases, judges said confessions, which defendants made during interrogation but later recanted, lacked credibility. After today's verdict, the court freed <PERSON> Masao </PERSON> <PERSON> Akabori </PERSON>, 59, who had been sentenced to death by a district court in 1958. The sentence was upheld by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in 1960, but a retrial began in 1987 in the <ORGANIZATION> Shizuoka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> after four appeals by <PERSON> Akabori </PERSON>. `` I am glad I won the appeal because I am innocent. And I am so thankful to my lawyers and all the people who have supported me and encouraged me through the past 35 years,'' <PERSON> Akabori </PERSON> said in a statement. His lawyers said he managed to avoid hanging because of an active support group. Such a long stretch on death row is rare but not unprecedented in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Akabori </PERSON> was arrested two months after 6-year-old <PERSON> Hisako </PERSON> <PERSON> Sano </PERSON> was kidnapped and strangled March 10, 1954, near her home in <LOCATION> Shimada </LOCATION> about 125 miles west of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Under police questioning, he confessed to the crime, but he later withdrew the confession and pleaded innocent. Today's verdict by a three-judge panel said <PERSON> Akabori </PERSON>'s confession lacked credibility, and there was no other credible evidence linking him to the crime. <PERSON> Akabori </PERSON>'s lawyers said he is entitled to $ 930,200 in government compensation for his wrongful time behind bars.
