<HEAD>Don't Disturb Breeding Turtles, Sultan Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Sultan </PERSON> <PERSON> Qaboos </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION> has banned tourists from sea turtle nesting beaches to allow the endangered species to breed in private, a newspaper reported Tuesday. <PERSON> Qaboos </PERSON> decreed that no one is allowed to watch the turtles in the area around <LOCATION> Ras </LOCATION> <LOCATION> al </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hadd </LOCATION>, about 125 miles south of the capital, <LOCATION> Muscat </LOCATION>, according to the <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION> daily, the Observer. Campers have been disturbing the turtles and leaving trash along their nesting beaches, the largest in the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, the sultan said. These beaches are of `` national, regional and worldwide importance for the survival of this species which is threatened with extinction,'' he said. `` To prevent further disturbance of the turtles and damage to the environment, it has been decided that camping and turtle watching by day or night is prohibited,'' the decree said. A government survey conducted from 1977 to 1980 highlighted major nesting and breeding areas of the sea turtles. Omani rangers were trained to take over protection and control activities in 1979 so that the turtle population could be monitored properly.
