<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-GroundhogDay     01-31 0697</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Groundhog Day,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Candlemas: Time to Hope for Clouds and Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seasonal stirrings are about to lead the nation's groundhogs from their snug burrows in search of _ lady groundhogs. That's right, when the furry mammals set forth in midwinter they could n't care less about making weather predictions, researchers say. It's hormones that get them moving. Only the timing proves a boon for small town chambers of commerce which seek publicity by taking advantage of the appearance of the animals and the associated ancient weather folklore. Feb. 2, known as Groundhog Day in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, has been a time for weather prognostications for centuries. The date is also known as Candlemas in the Christian tradition, a feast somewhat overshadowed by the commercial hype in recent years. The popular idea of predicting winter's end from animal behavior extends back at least to the ancient Celts, and was spread by the Roman legions. Over the centuries farmers came to consider the celebration, occurring about halfway between the winter solstice and the spring equinox, a good time to try to make weather predictions, applying the theory that the rest of winter would be the opposite of that on Candlemas. `` If Candlemas be bright and clear, there'll be two winters in the year,'' goes one traditional British rhyme. `` If Candlemas bring clouds and rain, go winter, and come not again.'' Similar beliefs are reported from <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. So serious was this taken that some German farmers were said to have preferred to see a wolf in the stable than that Candlemas day be pleasant and clear. It was the Germans who settled in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> who brought to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> the tradition of predicting the weather on this date. In <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> they had looked to the first movements of hibernating bears, hedgehogs and badgers for weather predictions. On this side of the ocean the honor fell to the woodchuck _ also known as the groundhog or marmot. Woodchucks do begin to leave hibernation at this time of year _ at least in some parts of the nation. But scientists report that what's on the animals' minds is sex, not weather. The males come out of the burrows first, while female groundhogs wo n't awaken for a week or more. In the meantime, the males search for food and fight among themselves according to researchers in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. The folk belief, however, is that animals somehow know future weather and, if they end their hibernation and sally forth, spring is close. Thus developed the worry that a shadow might frighten the animal back into its home, leading to a prediction of six more weeks of winter. Most folks consider that bad news. In the more northerly areas of the country, however, some people are said to hope that the groundhog will see its shadow _ predicting that winter will last `` only'' six more weeks. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Naval Observatory, meanwhile, relays a report that sailors who have been stationed at <LOCATION> Guantanamo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> say local people in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> have a somewhat similar tradition. That is that around this date banana rats find a tree to climb and relax in. If they settle at a low level of the tree it will be a bad year for hurricanes, while rats climbing high in the trees means a mild hurricane season, the belief goes. For the more religious, the church observations on Feb. 2 are known as the Feast of the Presentation of the Lord and the Feast of the Purification of <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>. This celebrates the time when <PERSON> Mary </PERSON>, as required by Jewish law, went to the Temple in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> to be purified 40 days after giving birth to a son, and to present that son, <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>, to God. That presentation of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>, said to bring light to the world, helped lead to the custom of blessing, on this date, the candles destined to be used for the rest of the year. Hence, the name Candlemas. And even those candles extend the weather-folklore connection, with the superstition that a candle blessed on this date will protect a home if lighted during a thunderstorm.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
