<HEAD>EPA Nominee Promises Aggressive Enforcement of Environmental Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>, designated to head the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, promised today aggressive and timely enforcement of environmental laws, saying the environment can be protected without hindering economic growth. <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>'s nomination by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as head of the federal government's key environmental agency is expected to win early <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approval. His appearance today before the Environment and <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> prompted bipartisan praise from members. Sen. <PERSON> Quentin </PERSON> <PERSON> Burdick </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.D. </LOCATION>, committee chairman, called <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>, who is president of the World Wildlife Fund, `` a person ... who appreciates that a great nation must be a good steward of its land, its air, its water and its natural resources.'' `` I'm pleased to join the chorus of admirers and welcomers,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, noting that <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> was introduced to the panel by no fewer than five senators from three states. <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> told the senators that while he plans to enforce environmental laws aggressively `` whenever it is warranted to safeguard public health and environmental quality'' he also will seek to deal with environmental problems through consensus and cooperation. `` We no longer have the time or luxury of allowing the bitterness, the polarization, the wasted resources and other excesses'' that have marked the conflicts in recent yeas between environmentalists and industry. <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> said he has spent his career in the environmental movement `` advocating environmental protection and economic growth'' and added that he was `` convinced we can find it.'' <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> ticked off a list of priority issues facing the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> such as finding ways to come to grips with the problems of acid rain, depletion of the earth's ozone layer, global warming, ocean pollution and cleaning up toxic waste dumps. But he said the problems posed by acid rain are `` ahead of everything else'' and promised early <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> action to develop legislation aimed at dealing with the issue. `` We expect to offer a comprehensive proposal for congressional consideration as soon as possible'' aimed at achieving a `` substantial reduction of acid rain by the end of the century,'' <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> said. Several senators noted <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>'s desire to deal with environmental issues through consensus and expressed concern that the approach might lead to inaction on part of the EPA. `` Will you conciliate, mediate, negotiate away our environmental laws?'' asked Sen. <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON>, D-Mont., who nevertheless expressed support for <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>'s nomination Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lieberman </PERSON>, D-Conn., urged <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> to be `` an environmental advocate'' in the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration and allow the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> not to be a `` reluctant combatant as it often has been'' in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration `` You can count on me being an advocate,'' replied <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>.
