<HEAD>Writer Fernando Namora Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Author <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Namora </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s best-known novelists, died Tuesday after a 50-year literary career He was 69. <PERSON> Namora </PERSON>, who was proposed for the Nobel Prize in 1981, was an instigator of the neo-realist spirit in Portuguese literature that tried to capture the texture of rural life in the 1940s. He was born in the central Portuguese town of <LOCATION> Condeixa </LOCATION> in 1919, studied medicine in <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION> and became a doctor serving remote mountain locations. His experiences of the rough life of the mountain people in <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s Serra de Estrela region formed the basis for his early novels, including `` Mountain Doctor,'' which was translated into many languages. <PERSON> Namora </PERSON> wrote more than 30 books and several volumes of poetry. In 1988, President <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Soares </PERSON> awarded Namora the Order of <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> the Navigator, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s highest civilian honor.
