<HEAD>1989-90 Budget Calls for Billion Dollar Deficit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Finance Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> on Tuesday introduced a $ 30.7 billion budget for the 1990 fiscal year with a $ 1 billion deficit that was bigger than expected. The document presented to the <ORGANIZATION> Knesset </ORGANIZATION>, or parliament, calls for a 19 percent increase in the government's operating budget to be partly offset by a reduction in the development budget and increases in taxes and fees. Defense outlays are to rise to $ 5.9 billion in the fiscal year beginning April 1, from $ 5.05 billion in the current year. Part of the rise in military spending is to cover increased costs for countering the 14-month Palestinian uprising in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Dealing with the <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> revolt has been costing the government about $ 14 million a month. The budget is expected to win easy approval in parliament, where a coalition between <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>' <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc controls four-fifths of the seats. But tax increases and cuts in food subsidies have already brought an angry public response. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> has pledged to hold down federal spending. In announcing his economic austerity program on Jan. 1, he said the aim was to try to hold this year's deficit to the same level as last year's $ 833 million in red ink. He did not explain Tuesday why the goal was not attained, but he told parliament that `` We have learned that nothing feeds inflation more than a budget deficit. ... Therefore, we decided to cut the expected budget deficit.'' The nation's massive <ORGANIZATION> Histadrut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> federation </ORGANIZATION>, which represents about 80 percent of <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> workers, has pledged to oppose <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>' plan, contending it will increase unemployment and significantly raise food, transport and insurance costs that workers ca n't afford An announced earlier, the budget calls for reducing government subsidies for food and public transport. Fees for universities, hospitals and insurance are to increase, and new taxes will be imposed on cars and imported services. Israeli TV estimated up to 4,000 government workers could lose their jobs under the austerity program. The Israeli economy grew a sluggish 1 percent last year, down sharply from 5.2 percent growth in 1987. About half of the slowdown has been blamed on the uprising, which has reduced tourism, business investment and sales to the territories.
