<SECOND>AM-Utility Safety,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>OSHA Proposes New Protections for Electric Utility Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government proposed Tuesday to expand safety requirements at electrical utility companies and said the changes could prevent about one-third of the 75 work-related deaths in the industry each year. The proposal by the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> would cover 660,000 employees of electric utilities and related services, the government said. The regulations, subject to a public comment period before they take effect, were drafted in cooperation with the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brotherhood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a utility industry trade group. The guidelines would affect such routine tasks as using ladders to enter manholes as well as work on exposed electric lines by tree-trimmers and repair workers. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> said it would cost about $ 21 million to bring utilities in compliance. The regulations would not cover construction and telecommunications workers who face similar hazards. Those workers are covered by separate standards. The tighter rules were proposed for electric utility workers because they encounter far greater risk of electric shock and falls, <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. The proposal does not cover electric power plants not run by utilities but <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> said it was considering extending the rules at a later date to cover all electric power generation, transmission and distribution. The agency said full compliance with the regulations should eliminate 24 to 28 of the approximately 75 work-related fatalities each year among covered workers. More than 3,200 injuries also should be prevented, <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> said. Electric shock accounts for half the deaths and injuries in the industry. To protect workers from shock, the guidelines would require wider use of protective equipment such as insulating blankets, gloves and sleeves. A number of training and safety measures also are included in the proposed guidelines.
