<FIRST>r w AM-DentalX-rays     01-31 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dental X-rays,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>FDA Panel Develops Guidelines on Dental X-rays</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Food and Drug Administration panel said Tuesday that children with healthy teeth may need dental X-rays no more than once every year or two, and dentally healthy adults once every two or three years. The panel's guidelines, reported in the current issue of the Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, were prompted by concern among some experts about the frequency of dental X-rays, both overuse and underuse. `` Although the radiation risk from a dental X-ray is extremely low, our goal is to eliminate any unneeded radiation exposure,'' <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said in an news release on the guidelines Tuesday. `` Until these guidelines were developed, there were few concrete criteria a dentist could use in deciding when X-rays were needed,'' he said. Young also stressed the flexibility of the guidelines, saying `` these are not hard and fast rules. In deciding whether an X-ray is needed, the dentist must use clinical judgment in evaluating the patient's needs.'' The guidelines say children and adults generally do not need X-rays each time they see a dentist if they are not at high risk and show no signs of dental disease. High-risk patients include those with enamel defects, poor dental hygiene or inadequate exposure to fluoride, or those who come from families with poor dental health. The guidelines say that children visiting a dentist for the first time will need X-rays. Most children who have not developed cavities and do not show any other symptoms of dental disease will need X-rays generally once every year or two, according to the guidelines. X-rays also are sometimes needed to check on the proper growth and development of permanent molars. The panel's guidelines are supported by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dentistry </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radiology </ORGANIZATION>, the American <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pediatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dentistry </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Periodontology </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> said.
</TEXT>
