<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> called President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` a very good and old friend'' Tuesday and said the two have only minor differences concerning the conduct of economic policy. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> played down reports of a rift between the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> which surfaced last week after <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in an interview he did not believe the central bank should be trying to slow economic growth because of a fear of inflation. `` Whatever differences do exist _ and I think they are minuscule _ have been exaggerated,'' <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said during an appearance before the congressional <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. In an interview, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had cautioned the central bank against overreacting to the threat of inflation following testimony the previous day by <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> in which the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> chairman said the risk of higher inflation was serious enough that <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> policy should err more on the side of `` restrictiveness than of stimulus.'' In his comments, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` I do n't want to see us move so strongly against fear of inflation that we impede growth.'' On Friday, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said during a press conference he did n't believe the differences between the new administration and the central bank were that great. Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarbannes </PERSON>, D-Md., said he was concerned that disagreements between <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> were being aired publicly rather than being worked out in private He questioned <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> about his access to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and the role he has had in making suggestions on what should be in the budget <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will submit to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> next month. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said he had not met with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> since December but that he was meeting on a regular basis with <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s top economic spokesman. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said he expects to be consulted on the contents of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget before the president unveils it in a joint address to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Feb. 9. `` I have no problem communicating with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. He is a very good and old friend of mine,'' <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said. `` I am not the least bit concerned about what is going on. I think the press is trying to make this a cause celeb where none exists.'' Many private economists have said the new administration, which needs robust economic growth to drive the budget deficit down, could be on a collision course with the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>, which since last March has been pushing interest rates higher in an effort to slow the economy and keep inflation from getting out of hand. In his comments Tuesday, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> sought to minimize any differences he might have with the new administration. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said the economic predictions used by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to construct its final budget were optimistic but were `` well within the range of reasonableness,'' especially if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration agree on significant spending cuts that will meet the Gramm-Rudman deficit reduction targets. Those targets call for reducing an expected $ 161 billion deficit this year to $ 100 billion in the fiscal year which begins Oct. 1. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> budget director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> has indicated the new administration will base its own budget revisions on the optimistic forecasts contained in the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> budget. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said that while he expects that the current economic recovery, which has lasted a peacetime record of six years, will some day end in a new recession, he said the imbalances that normally preceded a downturn were not now in evidence. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> said that rather than pushing the economy into another downturn, he believes the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to boost interest rates would extend the length of the recovery by keeping inflationary forces under control. On another matter, <PERSON> Greepspan </PERSON> said the huge <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit, which has shown little improvement over the past six months, would begin improving again this year without the need for a further drop in the value of the dollar.
