<HEAD>Speed Opening New Refinery Because of Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT HARCOURT, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials are trying to speed up the opening of the nation's fourth oil refinery because of shortages created by a fire at a nearby facility. The Jan. 24 blaze killed five people and destroyed a facility that had been producing 60,000 barrels a day. The cause of the fire was not known. Although the government diverted oil supplies from the north, long lines formed at gasoline stations in several cities in the heart of the oil-producing region. The fourth refinery, built to handle 200,000 barrels of petroleum daily, was scheduled to open March 16. The government set up a task force to speed up the opening of the new refinery. <PERSON> Aret </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, managing director of the <ORGANIZATION> Nigerian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said replacing the destroyed refinery would cost $ 300 million. It was opened in 1965 by British Petroleum. Production from the new $ 850 million refinery had been scheduled to go to overseas markets. Until the lost production capacity is replaced, however, about half of it will be sold in <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> or neighboring countries.
