<SECOND>AM-Runway Traffic,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>JFK Airport Uses Stoplights to Control Jet Traffic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airport </ORGANIZATION> has become the first airport in the country to install traffic lights on its runways and taxiways to reduce chances of a ground collision. Officials said Tuesday the experimental system is working well. The red light-green light system initiated Jan. 15 is intended to backstop the air traffic controllers who direct the movement of about 500 airplanes a day on the airport's nine miles of runways and 28 miles of taxiways. `` So far the feedback has all been positive,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Gartner </PERSON>, manager of aeronautical services for the <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> JFK </LOCATION>. `` They -LRB- pilots -RRB- are apparently pleased to see this as a supplement to the verbal commands when they cross the runways.'' Similar systems are functioning at <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>'s Main airports and have been recommended by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> to guide airplanes and ground equipment in bad weather. The $ 600,000 cost of the system was shared by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Port </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, which operates the airport. The system is being tested at 15 of the most critical intersections where taxiways cross runways. In all, there are about 75 places where taxiways cross runways, <ORGANIZATION> Gartner </ORGANIZATION> said. The need for such a system has been underscored by the increasing number of ground collisions at airports around the world. The worst such collision occurred in 1977 at <LOCATION> Tenerife </LOCATION> on the <LOCATION> Canary </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> and killed 583 people. The traffic lights are radio controlled from the tower, said <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON> <PERSON> Pardue </PERSON>. In the tower, a person called the local controller instructs all aircraft on the ground. With the new system, a second controller monitors conversations between the local controller and the pilots and operates the red and green lights accordingly. `` It will remove a chance for error where the pilot and the controller do not understand each other, or do n't communicate for some reason, or where the pilot hears clearance for a plane that he think is his, but is n't,'' <PERSON> Pardue </PERSON> said. `` Voice control will still govern, however. If the light is red, the pilot has to ask about it,'' <PERSON> Pardue </PERSON> said. He said it was too early to say whether the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> would eventually mandate such systems as busy airports.
