<HEAD>Sharansky: Human Rights Activist in Search of Unity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Sharansky</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Natan </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON>, Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s choice to represent <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, is a short, balding man who spent nine years in Soviet prisons but seems never to lose his sense of humor `` I will say only what I want to say. I have enough experience with interrogations and I know how to give answers,'' <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON>, 41, told a radio interviewer who pressed him to comment on the reported appointment. In the early 1970s, <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON>, a mathematician by profession, was a member of a human rights watchdog organization headed by physicist <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, a Nobel Prize laureate. <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> gained prominence as a spokesman for the group. He had wide contacts with foreign journalists in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and emerged as a champion of the Soviet Jewry emigration movement. <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> married in 1974. A day after the wedding, his wife, <PERSON> Avital </PERSON>, left for <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, hoping that he would soon follow. But <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> was denied exit visa. In March 1977, he was arrested and in 1978 convicted of espionage and sentenced to 13 years in prison. He spent nine years in Soviet prisons and labor camps and became a symbol of the Soviet Jews' plight, thanks to the efforts of <PERSON> Avital </PERSON>, who tirelessy campaigned on his behalf in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. Freedom came on Feb. 11, 1986, when <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> was released in a dramatic East-West spy swap on <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s Glienicke Bridge. In <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> first kept a low profile, devoting himself to family life. He and <PERSON> Avital </PERSON> now have two daughters, 2-year-old <PERSON> Rachel </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hannah </PERSON>, born in November. <PERSON> Avital </PERSON> became an observant Jew during the years of <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON>'s forced absence, but <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> has defines himself as non-religious Newspapers have speculated the marriage may fail apart because of religious differences. <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON>, for whom unity is a prime value, responded angrily to the reports. `` I feel like my own bald pate has been conscripted into <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s Kulturkampf,'' or culture war, he said in a recent interview `` People here concentrate too much on their differences ... instead of principles and common aims.'' <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> has successfully defeated attempts by many of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s parties to lure him into their political embrace But besieged by his former compatriots, he emerged last year to found a lobby group that seeks to improve conditions for thousands of Soviet immigrants plagued by shortages in jobs and housing. Unity, again, was the key, and Soviet Jewry activists said only <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> could unite about 10 groups representing the immigrants.
