<SECOND>AM-Bush-Budget,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration To Propose Package Of Tax Breaks In Revised Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration will propose a round of tax breaks reflecting campaign promises in its Feb. 9 budget rewrite, but disagreement has surfaced over a major component, a reduction in the capital gains tax, officials said Tuesday. Administration budget writers have not reached a consensus on whether the lower rates urged by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> during his campaign should apply equally to the sale of homes, stocks and other assets, said sources who spoke on the condition of anonymity. Treasury officials hope to minimize any adverse effect on the budget deficit that might result from lowering the tax on certain assets, such as private real estate and art objects. Sources said it is likely that the budget plan <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> unveils at the time of his address to a joint session of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> next week also will include: _ A child-care tax credit of up to $ 1,000 per child that would be available to low-income families, generally those earning less than $ 10,000 a year _ New tax incentives for oil and gas exploration, likely coupled with a call for removal of remaining price controls on natural gas, now affecting about 40 percent of production _ A proposal for tax-free `` enterprise zones'' to be established in some inner city areas to promote commercial growth, a program championed on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s nominee for Housing and <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> secretary, former Rep. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N </LOCATION> In addition, administration officials are still wrestling with terms of a package to help bail out troubled savings and loan institutions, and it appeared likely that some variation on a proposal for an increased fee for deposit insurance would be part of the new <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> budget plan. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said even before he took office that his campaign vow to propose a reduction in capital gains tax rates would be part of the budget revisions he makes to the $ 1.15 trillion spending plan for fiscal year 1990 that former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> submitted Jan. 9. And <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> reiterated his support for such a plan in a news conference last Friday. However, sources say there is still disagreement over exactly what form the tax cut should take. Capital gains _ profits from the sale of real estate, stocks and other assets _ are currently taxed at the same level as other income, at 15 percent, 28 percent or 33 percent, depending on overall income. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would lower the rate to a maximum of 15 percent. He claims that such a move would be an incentive to investment, generating up to $ 4 billion a year in new revenues. However, many leading economists, including the bipartisan <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, argue that lowering the tax would have the opposite effect _ reducing revenues and further worsening the budget deficit. To make sure the proposal does have the potential for spurring investment, administration budget writers are trying to fine-tune it. For instance, while it could be argued that a lower capital gains rate for the sale of coprorate stocks and commercial properties might spur additional investment, it might be more difficult to argue the same for the sale of private homes and objects of art, analysts suggest. The package of tax breaks to be included in <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget plan all reflect promises he made during last year's presidential campaign. However, White House officials say it seems unlikely that all of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s promises will make it into the document _ budget constraints being what they are. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> must propose a plan that will get the federal budget deficit, currently hovering at about $ 150 billion, down to below the Gramm-Rudman target of $ 100 billion for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1. And, he has repeatedly vowed, he will do it without proposing new taxes. `` Obviously we'll be setting priorities. I think you'll see education, environmennt, child care,'' said a senior White House official, insisting on anonmymity. On education, the official said the budget plan would highlight `` a few guiding principles,'' such as excellence and achievement and accountability and choice of schools. However, some of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign promises on education _ including a $ 500 million National Merit scholarship program, an expansion of the Head Start program and a $ 50 million increase in school experimentation _ may be considerably pruned back, sources said. The sources also said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign proposal to expand Medicaid coverage to more lower-income Americans and to allow low-paid workers to purchase it was being given a low priority in budget preparation talks. `` There's no question <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants to make this a kinder, gentler nation. But he also wants to reduce the federal deficit. The two have to be reconciled,'' said the senior White House official. Budget Director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> have been meeting almost daily to discuss key budget decisions, according to <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aides.
</TEXT>
