<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge said Tuesday he probably will allow the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to return to a policy of restricting political asylum applicants to southern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> pending reviews. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Filemon </PERSON> <PERSON> Vela </PERSON> extended until Feb. 20 an order blocking the procedure, but added: `` At that time, unless I'm persuaded otherwise, the restraining order will be lifted. `` We're pleased with the results,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON>, associate general counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION>, who traveled from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for Tuesday's hearing. `` The judge was fair.'' <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> critics cited a sharp increase in homeless Central Americans living in squalid conditions in the area after the procedure took effect Dec. 16. A group of immigration attorneys sued the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> over the matter here on Jan. 6, and on Jan. 9 <PERSON> Vela </PERSON> issued a temporary restraining order blocking the procedure. Under the procedure, the district began requiring asylum applicants to file their claims in <LOCATION> Harlingen </LOCATION> and await decisions there in 30 days, a period in which they were not allowed to work. The most visible effect of the travel restriction was a rugged campsite east of <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION>, where more than 300 Central Americans camped out on the ground under discarded cardboard and sheets of plastic. Huge case backlogs in cities such as <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> made it necessary to keep the immigrants near their points of entry while the government sorted out thousands of unfounded asylum claims, the government maintains. The only issue <PERSON> Ve