ut officials from the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> area visited southern <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> to tell the refugees they had no shelter for them, and joined officials in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> in calling on the federal government for help. <PERSON> Vela </PERSON> said he was concerned with past asylum statistics showing that, of the thousands who traveled into the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interior, 75 percent never showed up at <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> offices to legally pursue their cases. More than 30,000 Central Americans, about half of them from <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, passed through the <LOCATION> Harlingen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> in 1988, most having crossed the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION> illegally in the vicinity of the border city of <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION>.
