<HEAD>Brady Testifies on Buyout Tax Law Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> gave a qualified endorsement Tuesday to limiting tax deductions for interest payments on debt incurred in leveraged buyouts, if the resulting revenue were used to reduce taxes on stock dividends. `` If you're going to make a change _ and clearly we're not suggesting one _ we would suggest that you look in the area of perhaps limiting interest deductions and using that money to give a break to corporate owners of stock,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. Echoing his testimony last week before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration would prefer <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> `` wait a little'' to see if the trend of leveraged buyouts, which approached $ 100 billion in 1988, begins to diminish on its own. `` We have a habit of correcting things just as they are about to correct themselves,'' <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> said. `` If we wait a little longer, this thing is not going to gobble us up. We ca n't prove at this point that the economy has been damaged.'' Congressional Democrats, however, made it clear they're under pressure to rein in junk-bond-financed corporate takeovers, particularly because insurance companies and other holders of long-term, investment-grade bonds are beginning to be hurt in the deals. For example, owners of some $ 5 billion in long-term bonds in <ORGANIZATION> RJR-Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, saw the value of those securities drop by a $ 1 billion to $ 4 billion almost overnight upon the announcement of its pending takeover by buyout specialist <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> last fall for $ 25 billion. `` I have a feeling that we're looking at a <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale that's showing zero and then we have an eruption of 7 or 8 on the scale and it's too late,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Downey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, using a major earthquake with widespread, heavy damage as a metaphor Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., the panel's chairman, said the outcry for congressional action has become deafening in the 16 months since then-Treasury Secretary and now Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> tried to blame the 1987 stock market crash on an attempt then to curb leveraged buyouts through tax law changes <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> agreed that the `` driving force'' behind the buyout phenomenon is that companies can avoid a 34 percent corporate income tax rate by raising their capital through debt rather than stock sales. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> also has been attempting to find a way through <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> regulations or a legislative proposal to make the tax treatment of stock-equity and bond-debt financing more equal, saying the buyout problem would disappear with a `` level playing field.'' `` So far we have n't been able to come up with one,'' he said, adding that the financial community's response to his appeals for suggestions has been `` disappointing.'' Rep. <PERSON> J.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, likened <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>'s qualified endorsem