<HEAD>Memo Says Park Service Staffers Fought Fires Unenthusiastically</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Denis is correct</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> staffers in <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> fought last summer's forest fires so unenthusiastically that critics might well charge them with illegal use of funds, according to an internal memo given to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday. The Aug. 15 memo was written for the western regional director by <ORGANIZATION> Sequoia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> fire specialist <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON>, who paid a one-week visit to Yellowstone starting last July 28 to help project the courses of the fires. On July 21, <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON> ordered the service to drop its `` let it burn'' policy and fight all fires. By the time snow arrived in late September, more than 700,000 acres, a third of the park, had been burned over, though the service says almost all of that will quickly rejuvenate. Under the `` let it burn'' policy, fires that met certain conditions were supposed to be allowed to burn themselves out, but fires that threatened lives or developed areas or areas outside the park were supposed to be fought. The <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, part of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, conducts commercial timbering on most land adjacent to <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, and fights all fires there. `` The tactics used for these fires might well result in the suggestion that <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> was using suppression dollars to achieve natural resource benefits, a patently illegal use of these funds,'' said the <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> memo. Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Marlenee </PERSON>, R-Mont., submitted the memo at a joint hearing of the national parks subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the forests subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> On the memo, another official, <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Kilgore </PERSON>, chief of resource management and research in the western region of the service, had written, `` Perhaps not circulated widely at this time ... until we get our act together.'' Projections made on July 3 by the <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> staff `` showed, as we did, that the Fan fire would eventually leave <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> and burn <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> lands. Yet no firm suppression action was taken until the fire was within a mile of the boundary,'' <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> wrote. The memo said the Yellowstone staff often `` seemed to be satisfied to call the ... park boundary the confinement line'' corresponding to natural boundaries that could be relied on to check fires, `` although few natural barriers could be found there.'' After <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON>'s order, `` in spite of millions being spent and 2,000 fires, <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> staffers were bemoaning the fact that new starts, as mandated by the secretary'' had to be fought, the memo said. Despite his criticisms, <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said the fires had improved the ecosystem of the park. <PERSON> Marlenee </PERSON> said the memo showed that <PERSON> Hodel </PERSON>'s policy was `` not being carried out,'' though it did not make specific allegations that the secretary's order was disobeyed. <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Galvin </PERSON>, deputy director of the park service, said points raised in the memo would be `` absolutely'' checked out by an internal investigations team. <PERSON> Marlenee </PERSON> and other members of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have accused the park service of disregarding the interests of residents dependent on tourism through the `` let it burn'' policy.
