<HEAD>Wind Damage to Land Worse in November, December</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wind damage to land in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> is up sharply, reflecting the 1988 drought that hit much of the nation in the spring and summer, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. Wilson Scaling, chief of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Soil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said nearly 2.2 million acres were reported damaged in November and December, up more than 80 percent from 1.2 million acres in the same two months of 1987. `` A lot of the damage is a result of drought,'' Scaling said. `` The reasons vary by area, but major factors are lack of -LRB- crop -RRB- residue and poor vegetative cover _ both caused by a lack of moisture.'' Scaling said more than 80 percent of the land reported damaged was cropland, the remainder primarily rangeland. <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> accounted for more than 30 percent of the erosion damage in November and December with 664,128 acres. Scaling said that in addition to the damaged land in November and December, nearly 19 million acres were `` in condition to blow,'' with five months still remaining in the critical wind season. November and December are the first two months of an annual seven-month season when winds are highest and the soils are driest in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>. Surveys were made in 541 counties of the 10-state region. Although the 1987-88 season began with relatively light damage, it picked up as moisture conditions worsened. When the season ended last May 31, more than 13 million acres had been damaged, the second-largest acreage since the agency began records in 1935. The most widespread was in 1955 when about 16 million acres of <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> land were damaged by wind. Another bad year was 1980-81 when 12.5 million acres were damaged. According to the survey, the state-by-state breakdown comparing damaged acres in November and December with the damage during the same two months of 1987-88, included: _ <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, 28,795 acres damaged this season and 17,070 in 1987-88 _ <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, 135,550 and 31,520 _ <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, 510,875 and 304,023 _ <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, 54,405 and 74,590 _ <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, 51,100 and 3,300 _ <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, 188,200 and 230,000 _ <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, 68,480 and 31,288 _ <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, 112,250 and 69,400 _ <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, 664,128 and 250,220 _ <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, 346,754 and 190,885
