 <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> has kept a low profile in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Last year, he founded a lobby group that seeks to improve conditions for thousands of Soviet emigres plagued by shortages in jobs and housing. He has stayed out of politics and said in a recent interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that he had not found his place in any of the parties. He was critical of the divisiveness in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 120-member <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> that has 15 parties and said he would like to see the electoral system changed. `` I'm concern that everything in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> is partisan. I'd like to see more mutual values and consensus in party politics,'' <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> said. At the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> may find himself being called on to defend <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s strong tactics in trying to quell the nearly 14-month Palestinian uprising in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Arab groups once sought his support in vain, he said. `` To say that because <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> was against the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> this should also make him against the Israeli government, this is n't true. There is no parallel between them,'' he said. <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> said he investigated complaints about <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s behavior in the territories and defended the stance of his new homeland. `` For a country in a state of war, you can not have the same rules as for a country not at war. But it is important to keep democracy,'' <PERSON> Sharansky </PERSON> said.
