<HEAD>Cotton, Rice Subsidies Paid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal subsidies totaling almost $ 1.3 billion are being paid to cotton and rice farmers for taking part in 1988 acreage programs, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hertz </PERSON>, executive vice president of the departments <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said eligible producers of upland cotton will receive final deficiency payments of $ 725 million under the 1988 program. The rice payments total $ 570 million, he said. Deficiency payments are made under a formula to make up the difference betwen a target price for a commodity and an average of market prices or the government price support loan rate, whichever is higher. In the case of cotton, for example, the market price average was 56.5 cents per pound, or higher than the support level of 51.8 cents. The target was 75.9 cents. Thus, the `` deficiency'' payment is 19.4 cents per pound. For rice, the target was $ 11.15 per 100 pounds. The market price average of $ 6.84 exceeded the loan rate of $ 6.63, so the deficiency payment is 4.31 per hundredweight.
