 The newspaper Vorwaerts -LRB- Forward -RRB-, which survived bans by <PERSON> Bismarck </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> and championed Social Democratic causes for 112 years, is folding because of heavy financial losses, the party said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has spent about $ 27 million since 1970 to cover the weekly newspaper's losses. But rising costs and falling circulation forced the party to close the newspaper, party treasurer <PERSON> Hans-Ulrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Klose </PERSON> told reporters. The decision, reached `` with a heavy heart,'' came after it became clear that the leftist-liberal newspaper would not be able to raise its circulation of 46,000 by 50 percent. The weekly's staff of 44 will lose their jobs when the last issue goes on sale on Saturday. Founded in 1876 by <PERSON> Wilhelm </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasenclever </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wilhelm </PERSON> <PERSON> Liebknecht </PERSON>, Vorwaerts stopped appearing for 12 years when Chancellor <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Bismarck </PERSON> banned the Social Democrats in 1878. Vorwaerts took a strong anti-Nazi line and was banned by <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> in 1933. Its staff went into exile and continued to publish in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> and then <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> until German troops marched into <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> in 1940. The newspaper returned to <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> soil in September 1948 as the official organ of the Social Democratic party. The national printers trade union criticized the decision by the party's leadership to fold the paper, saying the public was losing `` an important voice.''
