 Somali Prime Minister <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Samater </PERSON> said Tuesday his government has taken a series of steps designed to achieve peace and prosperity internally and to improve relations with its neighbors. <PERSON> Samater </PERSON> spoke in an interview at the outset of a visit partly aimed at refuting allegations that <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> has engaged in widespread human rights abuses while attempting to put down an insurrection in the northern part of the country. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has imposed sharp cutbacks in aid to <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> as has the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. An Australian-based aid agency pulled out of <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> three weeks ago, citing political repression. But <PERSON> Samater </PERSON> said, `` Our position is that we have not committed human rights abuses.'' <PERSON> Samater </PERSON>'s visit is part of a diplomatic offensive the Somali government has initiated in an effort to bolser its international image. He will meet with Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Crocker </PERSON> on Wednesday and also plans consultations on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. As evidence of <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>'s new approach, <PERSON> Samatar </PERSON> said all political prisoners, numbering between 200 and 250, are being released and that steps have been taken to ensure that persons detained on suspicion of criminal conduct have a prompt judicial proceeding. He also said that state controls over the economy are being eased in order to revitalize the country's productive capacity. In addition, he said the government is willing to move toward a political settlement with the northern-based insurgency. <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> has enjoyed close political and military ties with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for years but many in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> were appalled last year over a reported dramatic increase in human rights abuses. Under congressional pressure, the administration placed a hold on about $ 55 million in economic assistance. <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Burkhalter </PERSON>, who monitors the rights situation in <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION> in her role as associate director of <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Watch </ORGANIZATION>, a private group, disputed <PERSON> Samatar </PERSON>'s account about the situation in <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>. `` It's very, very serious indeed,'' she said. `` The fact that nearly half a million Somalians left their country for the dubious privilege of refuge in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> says more than anything else about human rights conditions in <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>.'' In addition, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> last month decided to withhold food aid from an estimated 400,000 Ethiopian refugees in <LOCATION> Somalia </LOCATION>, contending that Somalian authorities were using the Ethiopians for military activities. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> finding had been corroborated in interviews with eyewitnesses. But <PERSON> Samatar </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>'s own figures show that 77 per cent of the Ethiopian refugees are women or children and that the rest are too aged to fight. `` Only a small percentage is able bodied,'' he said.
