<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, complying Tuesday with a request by governors in three coal-producing states, dropped a strike deadline and said its 1,700 workers at <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> mines would continue working without a contract. At the same time, the union expanded its effort to pressure <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> through protests and other actions aimed at the company's business partners, announcing a boycott of Virginia-based <ORGANIZATION> Crestar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and its banks Despite the decision not to strike at midnight Tuesday, union president <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Trumka </PERSON> had harsh words for <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> management and said he was `` not overly optimistic'' an agreement would be reached in the next 30 to 60 days, the extension period requested by the governors of <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Trumka </PERSON> accused <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> officials of failing to bargain seriously and of trying to break the union. <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> thanked the union for its action and, meeting a longstanding <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> request, said its chief executive officer, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, would accept <PERSON> Trumka </PERSON>'s invitation for a face-to-face meeting. <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> officials have sought the meeting because they contend company negotiators do not have the power to make concessions. <ORGANIZATION> Pittston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> President <P