<HEAD>Jury Hears Case on Earrings Made of Human Fetuses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury at the Old Bailey criminal court will decide whether earrings made of human fetuses are art or obscenity. Exhibit One, in a glass case, is a mannequin's head with a black curly wig, a scarf and a pair of human fetuses, of three to four months' gestation and freeze-dried, attached to its ears. Police seized the head Dec. 1, 1987, opening day of an exhibition of 40 items at the Young Unknowns art gallery in <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION>, south <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The show was called In Animal. Canadian sculptor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>, 36, the creator, and gallery owner <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Sylveire </PERSON>, 43, were charged with outraging public decency and causing a nuisance. They pleaded innocent, and this week a jury of 10 women and two men began listening to lawyers argue whether the work is art or outrage. <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, who represents <LOCATION> Sylveire </LOCATION> and sees the case as an important test of obscenity laws, said in court Monday one purpose of art is `` to shock and jolt the public from its complacency.'' He said the fetal sculpture could be seen as demonstrating that `` women wear abortions as lightly as they wear their earrings.'' Prosecutor <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Worsley </PERSON> said Tuesday the issue was not artistic merit or lack of it, but whether the earrings would shock, disgust or revolt a decent member of the public. He declared the fetuses, which were obtained from a pathology lecturer, to be an outrage to public decency. Sylveire was said to have told a journalist at the gallery he did not think the earrings were `` any more immoral than sculptors using human hair.'' <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> said he found the police reaction `` over the top'' _ too extreme. <PERSON> Worsley </PERSON> told the jury <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> `` saw nothing wrong with his work, but said that some people might have a moral objection to it.'' <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> legalized abortion in 1967, and the law allows abortions up to the 28th week of pregnancy.
