e new jets are designed as replacement for its current <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fleet of F-5s and F-15s, which is good at least until 1995. While the Europeans are offering the Saudis better financial terms than the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Saudis </LOCATION> are still attracted by the quality of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aircraft, which have been the mainstay of their arsenal, and the pilot training program offered by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the sources said. The Saudis are also seeking to avoid an embarrassing fight with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> over such a sale, which many on Capitol Hill oppose. Sen. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ariz </LOCATION>., last month put the administration on notice he would try to block an F-18 sale on the grounds it endangers <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> The two nations are technically still in a state of war. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administrations have both argued that persistent congressional rejections of such aircraft sales have driven the Saudis to look elsewhere, at the expense of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses and foreign policy interests.
