out whether they should infer intent on the basis of the victim's injuries even though they had been unable to find intent. `` We felt a simple one-word answer would have answered the question,'' the lawyer said. He noted that the jury came in a short time later. `` He chose not to say ` no,' and he chose to go into some long explanation which later, according to what the jury has told us, led to the conviction on manslaughter in the first degree,'' <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said. And allowing the jury to see the tape of Ms. <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON>'s injuries inflicted by <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> `` was a prejudice that I do n't know any criminal defendant could recover from.''
