w materials, here's your tractor and these are going to be your profits,''' <PERSON> Gurdian </PERSON> said angrily `` I am not going to work so the state can tell me how much I'm going to earn. I work to earn money.'' The Nicaraguan Democratic Coordinate includes four political parties, three labor unions and the <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Private </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION>. The opposition newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>'s speech left Nicaraguans disillusioned, and it called for reforms that would let them elect a new government `` that is more efficient and advantageous for the people.'' Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Venevision </ORGANIZATION>, a private television station in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> has asked <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> for economic aid. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> met with Venezuelan President-elect <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> after his arrival in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> for <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>' inauguration, scheduled for Thursday. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> provide cheap oil to some <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> and Central American nations under the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jose </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accord </ORGANIZATION>, begun in 1975 by <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> during his first presidency. But since 1982, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> stopped providing oil to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> because <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> did not pay its bills.
