<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One of two obstacles to low-power testing of the <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> nuclear power plant was cleared Tuesday when a federal board decided not to hold hearings on workers' performance during an emergency exercise. <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON>'s owners now can get their long-awaited low-power license if they prove that they can come up with $ 72.1 million to decontaminate and dismantle the reactor if it conducts the atomic tests but never operates commercially. The $ 5.8 billion Seabrook reactor was completed in July 1986 after years of delays and cost overruns. It remains idle because of evacuation-planning and financial obstacles. In a Dec. 21 ruling, the <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> set two conditions for low-power testing: establishment of the decommissioning fund, and a decision by one of its licensing boards on whether to open hearings on plant workers' performance during the two-day exercise in June. <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON> said Tuesday plant owners expect to submit a decommissioning-fund plan `` within the next couple of weeks.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Eichorn </PERSON>, chairman of the <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> owners' executive committee, said recently the owners are trying to buy a surety bond to meet the $ 72.1 million commitment. On procedural grounds, the licensing board Tuesday dismissed <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>'s request for the hearings, <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON> said. The plant is near the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> border, and six <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> communities lie within the plant's 10-mile evacuation plan. <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>'s request was based on an <ORGANIZATION> NRC </ORGANIZATION>