<HEAD>Epic McMurtry Western Turned into Four-Day Event for CBS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Durn </PERSON>. Just when you write off the whole danged network season, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> comes along with a big ol' event, a four-night masterpiece of a Western, `` Lonesome Dove.'' The eight-hour miniseries begins Sunday and runs through Wednesday. Readers who loved <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> McMurtry </PERSON>'s Pulitzer Prize-winning novel can be assured that <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> screenwriter <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Witliff </PERSON> has transformed it into a film that enlightens rather than obscures the heart of it. For viewers who have n't read the novel, the movie stands on its own. It's proof that the miniseries is still a worthwhile genre for epics like `` Lonesome Dove'' that ca n't be contained in a two-hour film. The cast is virtually unprecedented for a network movie _ Oscar-winners <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvall </PERSON> -LRB- `` Tender Mercies'' -RRB- and <PERSON> Anjelica </PERSON> <PERSON> Huston </PERSON> -LRB- `` Prizzi's Honor'' -RRB-, plus <PERSON> Tommy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON>, D.B. <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON>, <PERSON> Frederic </PERSON> <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON>, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Urich </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ricky </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroder </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Glenne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Headly </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanderson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Witliff </PERSON> wrote `` Raggedy Man'' and `` Country'' and co-wrote `` The Black Stallion.'' Director <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Wincer </PERSON>'s credits include `` Phar Lap'' and the network miniseries `` Bluegrass.'' But the miniseries belongs to <PERSON> Duvall </PERSON>. Well, the book did belong to <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> McCrae </PERSON>. <PERSON> Duvall </PERSON>, an actor who becomes his role, has found in coot-philosopher <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> a character who becomes the actor just as much. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> -LRB- with his hair dyed white -RRB- holds his own with <PERSON> Duvall </PERSON>, no mean feat. He has perhaps a more difficult role, as the simmering, taciturn Call. <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> and Call are legendary ex-Texas Rangers reduced to running a down-at-the-heels cattle outfit along the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION>, just outside a wide spot in the road called Lonesome Dove. When old companero <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Spoon </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Urich </PERSON> -RRB- shows up after 10 years, running from a fatal misunderstanding in <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, he's full of tales of a cattleman's paradise in a wilderness called <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>. Call, without Indians and outlaws to keep his mind off the ghosts of his past, figures an adventure is just what he needs, and he's soon rounded up 2,600 head of Mexican cattle and an inexperienced bunch of hands and headed off on a 3,000-mile trail drive <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> is usually satisfied to sit on the porch avoiding work, swigging whiskey and expounding loudly on any subject that happens to come up. But he goes along hoping to see his true love, <PERSON> Clara </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Huston </PERSON> -RRB-, who is married to a horsetrader in <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> trails along with <PERSON> Lorie </PERSON> -LRB- Lane -RRB-, a young prostitute who believes his promise to take her to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> sheriff <PERSON> July </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> -RRB- embarks reluctantly on a mission to bring <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> to justice. He is soon distracted, though, by the news that his wife -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Headly </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- has run off. She, too, is bound for <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, and an outlaw she still loves. Along the way, the cowboys tangle with sandstorms, stampedes, horse thieves and Indians. <PERSON> Lorie </PERSON> is stolen by Blue Duck -LRB- Forrest -RRB-, a vicious renegade who duels with <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> and meets an unusual demise. <PERSON> Witliff </PERSON> did an exceptional job of turning <PERSON> McMurtry </PERSON>'s vivid but often introspective 840-page book into a film, preserving the dialogue and improving the ending by a simple rearrangement of minor events. Much of the violence and raunchiness of the book remains, though toned down for network TV. When <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> is under attack by Indians on the open plains, he stabs his horse to death to use him for cover. <PERSON> Wincer </PERSON> occasionally lapses into unnecessary slo-mo melodrama. But only occasionally. The action sequences are mostly superb. Set designer <PERSON> Cary </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> has turned the `` Lonesome Dove'' of imagination into a reality. And <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Milsome </PERSON>'s cinematography is evocative without being too darned purty. Witliff telescopes many events, so the miniseries gets going much more quickly than the book. By the end of the first night, the trail drive is under way and the first fatality has occurred at the <LOCATION> Nueces </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. By then, any viewer with a pulse should be hooked. In exchange for the quicker pace, the miniseries shucks some of the character development of the book. There's no way around that unless the network stretched the miniseries into a week. After four nights, viewers might wish that they had.
