<HEAD>The Rape of Rosebud: Colorizing ``Citizen Kane''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Mr. <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> was a man who got everything he wanted, and then lost it. Maybe <PERSON> Rosebud </PERSON> was something he could n't get, or something he lost. Anyway, I do n't think it would have explained everything. I do n't think any word can explain a man's life. No, I guess <PERSON> Rosebud </PERSON> is just a piece in a jigsaw puzzle ... a missing piece.'' _ `` Citizen <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By HILLEL ITALIE</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If <LOCATION> Orson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Welles </LOCATION> were alive today, he would likely be fuming about `` goats and monkeys.'' That's how the celebrated filmmaker of `` Citizen Kane'' often referred to <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> studio executives who tampered with his movies. It was a line from <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>'s `` Othello,'' and <PERSON> Welles </PERSON> was indeed a classicist and a genius. But despite his artistry and the acclaim he received after his brilliant work on 1941's `` Citizen Kane'' _ considered by many to be the greatest movie ever made _ he was never able to direct another <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> film without major interference from the front office. <PERSON> Welles </PERSON>, who died in 1985, often boasted that it was the only film that was never taken away from him. But even `` Citizen Kane'' is no longer immune to tampering. <ORGANIZATION> Turner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which infuriated filmmakers and movie buffs by colorizing `` Casablanca'' and `` It's a Wonderful Life'' among others, has announced plans to give <PERSON> Welles </PERSON>' classic the same treatment. Television entrepreneur <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> acquired the rights to the movie in 1985 when he bought <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> with its massive film library for $ 1.5 billion. Directors, including <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, the late <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Huston </PERSON> and <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>, and such actors as <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON>, took their fight against colorization to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, pushing for legislation to create a national film commission with powers over the color-enhancement computerized process. They have long argued that the process often destroys the original work of art, changing mood and intent. <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> has long argued that he's merely protecting his investment by tapping into a new audience for old movies of the 1930s and'40s _ young people who grew up on color TV. `` I like things in color. We see in color,'' <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> said. `` I'm colorizing ` Casablanca' just for controversy's sake Once people start watching the colored version, they wo n't bother with the original.'' However, while <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> presents his color versions on his two cable-TV networks, other commercial networks continue to show the black-and-white originals and attract large audiences. And colorized films have had only moderate success in video sales, according to <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Erol </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest independent video chain Sales figures for 1988 show that the colorized version of `` It's a Wonderful Life,'' by far the biggest seller, sold 2,000 units at the retail price of $ 8.95 For the black-and-white version, 10,705 sales, retailing at $ 4.95, were reported. Few colorized films are available for rentals. `` There's a market for both,'' <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> acknowledged. `` I think you have to keep in mind what's out there. Most of the young people grew up in a colored world while film buffs and afficionados want the originals.'' While two companies are coloring test scenes of `` Citizen Kane'' to see if the process is even feasible on the movie, critics continue to fume. `` It's nothing short of criminal. They're tampering with a masterpiece,'' said director <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON>, who helped edit `` Citizen Kane.'' `` If he -LRB- <LOCATION> Welles </LOCATION> -RRB- were alive today, he would be at somebody's throat He would be bombasting all over the place.'' While `` Citizen Kane'' made headlines at first when a brash, young <PERSON> Welles </PERSON> parodied the life of newspaper magnate <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Randolph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hearst </PERSON>, it is an unchallenged, magnificent work of art and technology because of its innovative use of lighting, camera and sound. While many movies had been made in color by 1941, notably `` Gone With the Wind,'' `` The Wizard of Oz'' and `` A Star Is Born,'' Welles considered black-and-white essential to setting the proper mood for his film. `` Orson always said a black-and-white film abstracts reality,'' recalled <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Leaming </PERSON>, who collaborated with <PERSON> Welles </PERSON> on his autobiography. `` The words he always used for <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> were ` hallucinatory' and ` dreamlike.' He said it created a mood several steps removed from the real world. `` For <LOCATION> Orson </LOCATION>, black-and-white was one the things that gave ` Citizen <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>' the possibility of being an art film. He said all of the elements were conceived in the same way. If you change one element, all of the other elements are going to look wrong.'' Although <PERSON> Welles </PERSON> had never made a feature film before signing a contract with <ORGANIZATION> RKO </ORGANIZATION> in 1939, he was already famous. In 1938, his notorious `` War of the Worlds'' radio broadcast convinced thousands of people that Martians had landed in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. His innovative stage productions with the Mercury Theatre and his work with <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>'s Negro Theatre, including an all-black presentation of `` Macbeth,'' made him the talk of <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>. He considered several sources for his first film. He had originally attempted an adaptation of <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON>'s short novel, `` The Heart of Darkness'' -LRB- later a source for <PERSON> Frances </PERSON> <PERSON> Coppola </PERSON>'s `` Apocalypse Now'' -RRB-, but the start of World War II in 1939 endangered the film's success in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, a market considered vital by RKO He also looked into making a comedy starring <PERSON> Carole </PERSON> <PERSON> Lombard </PERSON> or <PERSON> Lucille </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON> and a Mexican melodrama based on a novel by <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Calder-Marshall </PERSON> but then came up with on another idea based on conversations with his friend, <PERSON> Ashton </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, a drama critic for the Hearst-owned <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> American. <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> had intrigued <PERSON> Welles </PERSON> with his depictions of <ORGANIZATION> Hearst </ORGANIZATION>, whose parties at his <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Simeon </LOCATION> castle and extra-marital affair with the actress <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> were the talk of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>. Welles and <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Mankiewicz </PERSON> put together a script that chronicled the life of a newspaper tycoon and would-be politician, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>, who dies a lonely man after his attempts to make an opera singer out of his wife, <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, destroy his personal and professional life. -LRB- They won the Academy Award for best screenplay. -RRB- The film's plot centered on a reporter's efforts to determine the meaning of the dying <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>'s final word, `` Rosebud.'' For those who never saw the movie, <PERSON> Rosebud </PERSON> was the name of his sled. <ORGANIZATION> Hearst </ORGANIZATION> was the main source for `` Citizen Kane'' but <PERSON> Welles </PERSON> also drew upon the lives of obert <PERSON> McCormick </PERSON>, a wealthy <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> businessman who had himself tried to promote an untalented opera singer, and <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Infull </PERSON>, who had built an opera house in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Instead of a straightforward narrative, `` Citizen Kane'' jumps back and forth in time as the reporter interviews people who knew <PERSON> Kane </PERSON> and newsreels depict the highlights of his public life. It is similar in structure to `` Marching Song,'' a play <PERSON> Welles </PERSON> wrote when he was 17, based on a reporter's search for the abolitionist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. `` <LOCATION> Orson </LOCATION> was fascinated by a story within a story,'' said <PERSON> Leaming </PERSON>, a professor of theater and film at <ORGANIZATION> Hunter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. `` ` Citizen <PERSON> Kane </PERSON>' was a logical development.
