<FIRST>r f PM-HealthCosts Bjt   01-31 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Health Costs, Bjt,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>Health-Care Plan Costs Rise 18.6 Percent In 1988</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The lid on the cost of health-care plans popped off in 1988 as the expense per worker of employer-sponsored programs shot up 18.6 percent, a new survey says. The jump came after two years of moderate increases _ 7.7 percent in 1986 and 7.9 percent in 1987 _ and `` there does n't appear to be much relief in sight,'' according to a report released Monday by A. <ORGANIZATION> Foster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Higgins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a New York-based benefits consulting firm. Health insurers swallowed some of the unexpected cost increases last year and will pass them along this year, ensuring another stiff rise, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Erb </PERSON>, the managing consultant who conducted the survey. The average cost per employee of health care plans was $ 2,354 in 1988, up from $ 1,985 in 1987, according to the survey of more than 1,600 employers, whose plans cover a total of 10 million workers and dependents. The figures include the cost of plans to both employers and employees. The medical-care component of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Consumer Price Index rose 6.9 percent last year, making it the fastest-growing part of the inflation measure. But the cost of services is only part of the problem for employers and employees, <PERSON> Erb </PERSON> said. According to <PERSON> Erb </PERSON>, these were some of the factors in last year's big jump: _ Expensive medical services such as heart and liver transplants are becoming more widely available, so more people are using _ The federal and state governments, strapped for money, are holding down how much they pay health-care providers for <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> and Medicaid patients That forces the providers to raise their prices to other customers. _ Doctors are raising fees for outpatient services because patients tend to be more highly reimbursed for them and are less likely to complain The higher reimbursement was intended to encourage use of outpatient services, which are generally cheaper than hospital care. _ Doctors are requiring more follow-up visits, some of which may not be medically necessary `` The providers of care have gotten wise to some of the tricks and are compensating for it,'' <PERSON> Erb </PERSON> said in an interview. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. Ring, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said in response he did not see any evidence that doctors were reaping big fee increases from the shift to outpatient care. Ring, a family physician in <LOCATION> Mundelein </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, also said he would like to see statistics backing up <PERSON> Erb </PERSON>'s claim that doctors were requiring medically unnecessary follow-up visits. <PERSON> Erb </PERSON> said he did not have such statistics. The 1988 increase was smallest, 15.6 percent, for companies with under 1,000 employees, which usually pay for their plans through insurers. Insurers did not anticipate the big increase in expenses last year and are likely to put through big increases this year to compensate, <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON> said. To illustrate the increased availability of high-tech medical care, <PERSON> Erb </PERSON> said there are about 120 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> medical centers that can do heart transplants, up from 30 just two years ago. Also, he said, it has become common for hospitals to give heart-attack patients a dose or even two of TPA, a clot-dissolving drug that costs $ 2,000 a dose. `` ` Miraculous cures' are becoming more common,'' he said in a written statement. `` But miracles cost money.'' The cost of providing benefits for mental health and substance abuse shot up 27 percent in 1988 to an average of $ 207 per employee and now totals 9.6 percent of total medical plan costs, <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON> said. At the same time, more employees are screening prospective employees for substance abuse. Twenty-four percent screened at least some prospective employees last year, up from 20 percent in 1987, the survey found. <PERSON> Erb </PERSON> said health plans that require employees to share costs are usually successful in reducing costs to employers. But health maintenance organizations, which were touted as a way to rein in expenses, apparently have not succeeded as planned, he said. According to the <PERSON> Foster </PERSON> <PERSON> Higgins </PERSON> survey, 59 percent of employers said premiums paid to health maintenance organizations -LRB- HMOs -RRB- were as high as or higher than premiums under traditional health-care plans.
</TEXT>
