based in <LOCATION> Upper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Saddle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, touted its boxy subcompact cars as the cheapest new auto in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> when they went on sale in August 1985 at $ 3,995. Sales topped 39,100 in the first 10 months of 1987, but dropped to 26,000 in the same period of 1988, according to figures released by the company. Several calls placed Monday to the company were not answered. In its filing, <ORGANIZATION> Yugo </ORGANIZATION> listed $ 30.5 million in assets and the same amount in liability and equity. Global Motors listed $ 27.4 million in each category. <ORGANIZATION> Proton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> listed $ 10,000 in each. <PERSON> Mabon </PERSON> <PERSON> Nugent </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment banking company which invested $ 10.5 million in <ORGANIZATION> Global </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> and owns 33 percent of the company, said the bankruptcy filing was welcome. `` It is appropriate that the <LOCATION> Yugoslavian </LOCATION> manufacturer of the car has come forward with support necessary for the company to proceed. Hopefully, they will be able to complete a plan of reorganization and continue to serve Yugo dealers and customers,'' the banking concern said. Court papers said the filing was authorized by <PERSON> Marcel </PERSON> <PERSON> Kole </PERSON>, the company's chief financial officer and acting chief executive officer. He said the company is committed to doing business in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. In April 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Yugo </ORGANIZATION> had 300 employees and now has 60, <PERSON> Kole </PERSON> said.
