<HEAD>Short-Term Rates at 3-Week High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interest rates on short-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities rose in the government's latest auction to the highest level in three weeks. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sold $ 7.2 billion in three-month bills at an average discount rate of 8.33 percent on Monday, up from 8.26 percent last week. An additional $ 7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 8.39 percent, up from 8.31 percent last week. The rates were the highest since Jan. 9, when three-month bills sold for 8.36 percent and six-month bills averaged 8.48 percent. The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 8.63 percent for three-month bills with a $ 10,000 bill selling for $ 9,789.40 and 8.88 percent for a six-month bill selling for $ 9,575.80. In a separate report, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that the average yield for one-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable-rate mortgages, rose to 8.97 percent last week from 8.96 percent the previous week.
