<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Shamrock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has filed a lawsuit to block <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 1.1 billion stock buyback plan, which analysts believe was designed to thwart a hostile takeover by the television and radio concern. <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>, the Disney-owned company that has been pursuing <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> since last summer, filed suit Monday in <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The suit asks the court to prohibit both <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s buyback program and its plan to issue $ 300 million in convertible preferred stock, which also were announced on Monday. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> said it indicated it had invited two members of the investor group, <ORGANIZATION> Corporate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> L.P. </ORGANIZATION>, to join its board of directors. In its suit, <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> alleges <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s directors `` breached their fiduciary duties by issuing additional, dilutive voting securities to persons friendly to management in the face of <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>'s announced intention to wage a proxy contest at <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s upcoming annual meeting. Since July, the instant photography pioneer has been fighting a hostile buyout offer from Shamrock, which is offering $ 45 a share in a tender offer that values <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> at about $ 3.2 billion. <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>, a television and radio concern owned by the <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Disney </PERSON> family, also has indicated it will wage a proxy fight for control of <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s board at the company's annual meeting in May, and if successful would force the sale of <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> either under its offer or a higher third-party bid. <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> president and chief executive officer <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> called <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s actions irresponsible and a sign of entrenched management. `` The placement of preferred stock, together with the proposed stock buy-back program, is clearly a defensive action designed to park even more <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> shares in ` friendly hands' at the expense of <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s public shareholders,'' <PERSON> Gold </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> stock closed Monday at $ 40.62 -LCB-, up 62 -LCB- cents in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite trading. Polaroid spokesman <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Yanes </PERSON> denied the planned stock issue was a defensive move designed to discourage Burbank-based Shamrock's advances `` It's designed simply to deliver a portion of the company's current value while enhancing the growth prospects for its values,'' <PERSON> Yanes </PERSON> said Companies frequently buy their own stock to reduce the number of shares outstanding and to raise the stock price. Such practices have become common among companies seeking to discourage takeovers. Some analysts said <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION>'s stock buyback was unlikely to attract shareholders unless the market price of <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> stock tops <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>'s $ 45-a-share offer. `` There's no incentive for people to sell the <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> stock,'' said <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGA