<HEAD>Quarterly Earnings Up 22 Percent, Annual Rise 14 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday its net income for the fourth quarter rose 22 percent as the soft drink company benefited from increased international sales and a drop in costs. Annual earnings for the Atlanta-based company were up 14 percent, going over the billion-dollar mark for the first time in the company's 103-year-history. The previous record was $ 934 million in 1986 before the company spun off its bottling and movie subsidiaries. For the quarter ended Dec. 31, <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 235.5 million compared with $ 193 million a year earlier. After a $ 5.2 million deduction for preferred stock dividends, the earnings were 65 cents per share, compared to 52 cents in the 1987 quarter, when there was no preferred stock deduction. Fourth-quarter revenue edged up 1.8 percent to $ 2.03 billion from $ 1.99 billion a year earlier. The cost of goods sold fell 8.1 percent for the quarter to $ 912.8 million from $ 993.4 million. For the year, net income was $ 1.04 billion from $ 916.14 million in 1987. After a $ 6.43 million preferred stock dividend, earnings per share were $ 2.85, compared with $ 2.43 in 1987 when there was no preferred stock dividend. The company said foreign soft drink shipments grew 7 percent last year, led by combined volume and operating income increases of 26 percent in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and 12 percent in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. Domestically, soft drink concentrate and syrup shipments rose 6 percent and operating income was up 9 percent. Retail case sales advanced an estimated 5 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION>, which includes Hi-C and Minute Maid brands, had a 15 percent increase in volume for its boxed fruit juices. However, volume for frozen orange juice was down 22 percent and chilled orange juice volume fell 6 percent. The company reported a 34 percent increase in operating income growth for the division, however, because of a restructuring in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> reported a 57 percent decline in equity income because of lower earnings at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> resulting from the one-time writedowns associated with restructuring. In December 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary was combined with <ORGANIZATION> Tri-Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> to form <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which is now a free-standing company in which <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> owns 49 percent of the stock. <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> also owns 49 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the largest bottler of <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> products. Those two companies contributed $ 29.5 million in income for the quarter and $ 48.3 million for the year. During 1988, the company said it repurchased 18.9 million shares of common stock, decreasing outstanding shares by 3.4 percent. In all, the company has bought back 25.5 million of the announced repurchase of 40 million shares.
