<SECOND>PM-Fax Follies, Adv 03,0835</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Friday Feb. 3 and thereafter.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Facsimile Machines Transform Life But Can Create Headaches _ and
Lawsuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Facsimile machines, the latest office rage, have made it easier and possibly more fun for workers to work, stay in touch, and even order lunch, but they also have fallen prey to human goofs and greed. A presidential candidate used a fax machine to enter the race at the last minute. A <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> radio station accepts contest entries by fax _ and notifies winners the same way. But a leading retailer recently lost a $ 73 million lawsuit in federal court here partly because a confidential document was faxed to the wrong place, and irritation is growing as `` junk fax'' increases. Still, `` Once you have one you ca n't live without it, and you use it more and more,'' said <PERSON> Elliot </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, co-author of `` The Book of Fax: An Impartial Guide to Buying & amp; Using Fascimile Machines.'' The machines convert a page of information into an electronic format, then transmit it via telephone line to another machine on the other end, where it is decoded and printed. The average office fax costs $ 1,000 to $ 4,000. More than 4 million fax machines will be purchased by 1991, and sales are expected to grow at 30 percent a year well into the 1990s, according to King's book. `` To a lot of people the fax machine has become a fact of life in the office,'' said <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Crouse </PERSON>, advertising and promotion director for <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s WROR-FM. The radio station has been using the fax to entice office workers to listen. It has been running a contest asking workers to fax in the funniest thing found lying around the office. The chuckle of the day wins, with the victor receiving notification from the station via fax. `` They not only have to send us the fax, but they have to watch their fax machines to see if they've won,'' said <PERSON> Crouse </PERSON>. Office workers can also use the machines to place lunch orders at `` fax food'' restaurants. `` We do a lot of delivery and takeout and for them to just fax over their order, it goes through less hands and it keeps the order more correct,'' said <PERSON> Evie </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, manager of <PERSON> Maxine </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Seafood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cafe </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` It saves us in tying up phone lines.'' She said the restaurant, which got its fax machine in October, gets about half its takeout requests via fax, roughly 15 to 20 orders per day. The portable fax opens up a whole new world to faxaholics. `` I had a guy come in here once who wanted a portable one so he could take it golfing,'' said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Villaloando </PERSON>, owner of <ORGANIZATION> Citifax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Northbrook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>. Portable fax machines were used constantly during the presidential election, said <PERSON> Tad </PERSON> <PERSON> Devine </PERSON>, director of delegate selection for <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' Democratic primary campaign and campaign coordinator for vice presidential nominee <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> Both candidates traveled in planes equipped with fax machines. They also had portable fax for use in their hotel rooms, he said. Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> almost missed his chance to run for the Democratic presidential nomination when his filing papers failed to show up for the primary deadline. `` When it was not there late that afternoon, his campaign was contacted by the secretary of state in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Gephardt </PERSON>'s campaign sent in a fax,'' said <PERSON> Devine </PERSON> But fax fiascos can be expensive. A federal lawsuit that ended in a $ 73 million judgment against <ORGANIZATION> K </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> mart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> earlier this month was initiated when a clerk mistakenly faxed a confidential document to <ORGANIZATION> Fashion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a Pawtucket-based merchandise wholesaler. The document, an estimate of the commissions owed, was intended for K mart headquarters in <LOCATION> Troy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>. K mart is appealing the judgment `` It is a danger,'' agrees King. `` It's like mail without an envelope and you can make a lot of mistakes.'' Just like the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, junk mail is a problem. A <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> legislator recently proposed legislation that would ban the unsolicited use of fax machines to send advertising messages. `` It's a really effective way for people to direct sales and services,'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said, explaining the 10 percent return on mass faxings is more than double that of bulk mailings. In addition, the `` fax attacks'' cost the solicitor less money than mailings because there are no printing, envelope stuffing or postage fees. The owners of the targeted telecopier, however, gets stung $ 3 to $ 4 for the price of paper, printing and manpower, said King. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Fishman </PERSON>, <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s co-author, envisons another problem _ fax-a-porn. `` Some enterprising young person sometime will enter the business of pornography,'' he said. `` Call up and get a pornographic photograph'' faxed to you.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for PMs Friday Feb. 3</NOTE>
