<FILEID>AP-NR-01-31-89 1336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f AM-BusinessMirror Adv02   01-31 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Mirror, Adv 02,0766</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv02</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release AMs Thursday, Feb. 2</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cut The Capital Gains Tax?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It appears that <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wo n't give up on his idea of cutting the capital gains tax, which pretty much guarantees an explosive battle in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. That battle will erupt because capital gains are seen as something that involve the rich. But either that notion is false or millions of Americans now qualify as rich, and the list grows larger with every year. In truth, capital gains concern anyone who inherited or purchased a few shares of stock or a house or who in almost any other way built a financial estate through ingenuity, hard work or just luck. Under the 1986 tax act, the capital gains tax was raised from a maximum of 20 percent to 28 percent for all earners of capital gains. The increase was 40 percent for wealthy taxpayers, but 100 percent for many poorer taxpayers, who real capital gains rate was only 14 percent or 15 percent. It brought capital gains taxes in line with taxes on ordinary income. That was bad enough, said critics, who also observed other quirks in the situation _ that such taxes can be applied to income never made, to buying power that never existed, and to funds a taxpayer never got a chance to use. Definition: Capital gains are profits realized from the sale of capital assets such as securities or real estate. Often they involve risk, and usually they are the results of long-term investments. For this and other reasons, including the nation's need for such capital investments, gains generally were taxed at less than ordinary income. Consider the consequences now of taxing such long-term gains at the same rate as ordinary income _ income that is taxed during the same year in which it is earned. Assume an investment of $ 5,000 in stock held for seven years. If the appreciation averages 10 percent over that time the investor will have about doubled his money. The capital gains would be $ 5,000; the tax about $ 1,400. While it appears the invester earned 10 percent, he really earned only 6 percent because the value of the dollar changed in that time. Inflation eroded it at a rate of 4 percent a year, an assumption but a very safe one. At 6 percent a year money will not double in seven years. The $ 5,000 sum will grow to about $ 7,100 in buying power. But the investor will pay capital gains taxes as if it had grown to $ 10,000. He will pay $ 1,400 in taxes. Deducting the taxes from the inflation-adjusted total earned leaves him with just $ 5,600 or $ 5,700 _ an average annual gain of $ 100 or less for having risked his money and invested his savings in the American economy. The example is a modest one. Consider, for example, a person who put some money away back in 1970 with the idea of using it for retirement. The investment has since tripled in value to a very tidy sum. Or has it? Consumer price inflation in 1970 was 5.9 percent, followed by 4.3 percent in 1971, 3.3 percent in 1972. Not too bad, but then it hit 6.2 percent in 1973 and 11 percent in 1974. It never fell below 5.8 percent through 1978. Thereafter, the tale becomes grim. Three successive years of double-digit inflation hit, the worst of these years being 1980, when official consumer price inflation measured year to year struck 13.5 percent. By the year 1983, the value of the 1970 dollar had been cut in half and, of course, it has been cut additionally since then, even though inflation has been restrained to an `` acceptable'' 3 - to 5 percent a year The 1970 investor has allegedly tripled his money. Assuming an investment of $ 5,000, he now has more than $ 15,000, although sensible people know that in 1970 dollars it is worth less than half that, or about $ 7,000. Nevertheless, should that investor sell, he has a $ 10,000 capital gain on which taxes must be paid. And that tax will levied at the same rate at which money currently earned is taxed. that is, as if it had current buying power. In short, the investor will be liable for $ 2,800 tax on what in effect is $ 7,000 in terms of the 1970 dollar. He ends up with a net loss.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv AMs Thursday, Feb. 2</NOTE>
