 <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday reported a fourth-quarter loss of $ 12.8 million and annual profits of only $ 1.7 million, while its chairman forecast another disappointing year for 1989. The fourth-quarter results of the <LOCATION> Bloomington </LOCATION>, Minn.-based computer maker compared to net earnings in the same period a year ago of $ 10.8 million, or 26 cents a share. Sales for the quarter of $ 933 million were slightly ahead of last year's $ 927 million. It was the second consecutive quarter of losses after four profitable quarters. For the year, <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION>'s net income dropped to 3 cents a share on sales of $ 3.6 billion from the 1987 level of $ 19.3 million, or 45 cents a share, on sales of $ 3.4 billion. The computer maker suffered from poor results in its mainframe, supercomputer and semiconductor businesses, Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON> said. `` Although we anticipate the majority of <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> businesses to be profitable in 1989, the company's overall operating performance will continue to be disappointing until we fix the problems that undermined 1988 results,'' Price said. `` The goal for the coming year is to resolve those problems and lay a foundation that is the basis of strong performance in subsequent years.'' Mainframe computer shipments in 1988 were hurt by delays in getting critical logic ships from a supplier and by soft demand, especially in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, Price said. In July the company temporarily shut down several of its mainframe plants and temporarily idled 7 percent of its work force in response to the trouble. The company's new <ORGANIZATION> ETA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> supercomputer subsidiary had poor 1988 results, and semiconductor revenues were off partly because the data storage market continues to be weak, he said. <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Foltz </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the company, said layoffs, attrition and the sale of some businesses in 1988 resulted in a 2.3 percent decrease in <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION>'s work force from 34,500 employees at the end of 1987 to 33,700 at the end of 1988. In addition, the company has told its 27,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> employees that they must take five days off without pay in the first quarter of this year. Other changes at <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> included changes in top management in December, including the appointment of <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Perlman </PERSON> as president.
