<HEAD>GATT Panel Backs EEC In Dispute Over U.S. Trade Law</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An international trade panel has recommended the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> amend its Tariff Act of 1930 to make it comply with international trade rules, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. It said a disputes panel of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the world trade body, found Section 337 of the act violates international trade rules. The section deals with the right of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to rule on patent violations by importers. The disputes panel said by comparison patent violations of U.S.-produced goods go to federal court where accused parties have a better chance to defend themselves than those before the <ORGANIZATION> ITC </ORGANIZATION>. The panels' finding will be discussed by the full <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Feb. 8, <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Nico </PERSON> <PERSON> Wegter </PERSON> said. `` The commission is, of course, pleased with the fact that the panel shares the view of the commission'' that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> violates international trade rules. Officials at the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mission to the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> declined to comment on the ruling that was issued in December but was not made public unitil Tuesday. The panel's ruling stems from a 10-year-old dispute between <ORGANIZATION> Akzo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> NV </ORGANIZATION>, the Dutch chemicals group, and <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> over patent rights for aramid fibers. These synthetic fibers are used in the automotive, aerospace, defense and construction industries. In November 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> ITC </ORGANIZATION> blocked imports into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of <ORGANIZATION> AKZO </ORGANIZATION>'s aramid fibers saying the company had violated <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION>'s patent rights <ORGANIZATION> Akzo </ORGANIZATION> complained to the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> commission about the procedure used by <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> to seek protection from foreign competitors under section 337 of the Tariffs Act. In 1987, the commission found the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> law to amount to an unfair trade practice. It took the issue to <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> where a special disputes panel was formed later that year. The commission said Tuesday if the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, which is made up of officials of the 100 or so <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> member states, adopts the panel's report, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must take the `` necessary measures to rectify as quickly as possible the present situation. A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> EC </ORGANIZATION> chemical federation, <ORGANIZATION> Cefic </ORGANIZATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> AKZO </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> had settled their dispute while the investigation was continuing. He welcomed the ruling on Section 337 saying it represented was `` increasingly burdensome'' for <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> businesses and said the panel's ruling was `` a victory'' for the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>
</TEXT>
