<HEAD>Borden Posts 15.4 Percent Gain In Fourth-Quarter Profit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Borden </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday its fourth-quarter profit rose 15.4 percent despite drought-related costs that severely affected the company's dairy products earnings. For the three-month period ended Dec. 31, <ORGANIZATION> Borden </ORGANIZATION>'s net income totaled $ 93.9 million, or $ 1.27 a share, up from $ 81.3 million, or $ 1.10 a share in the year-earlier period. Revenue rose 9.9 percent to $ 1.98 billion from $ 1.8 billion in the 1987 quarter. For all of 1988, the giant food producer posted a 16.8 percent increase in after-tax profit to $ 311.9 million, or $ 4.22 a share, from $ 267.1 million, or $ 3.62 a share in the previous year. The company's revenue for the year totaled $ 7.2 billion, up 11 percent from $ 6.5 billion in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Borden </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> R.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ventres </PERSON> attributed the latest gains to `` internal business growth spurred by the benefits of acquisitions,'' including the purchase a year ago of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prince </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which makes pasta products. Strong performances by the company's <ORGANIZATION> Snacks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> and the Grocery and Specialty Products Division, including Eagle Brand products, were largely responsible for <PERSON> Borden </PERSON>'s yearlong gains, the company said. But drought-related costs resulted in a 12 percent slump in operating income for the company's dairy sector, to $ 102.3 million in 1988 from $ 116.3 million in 1987. <PERSON> Borden </PERSON> said profit margins were squeezed, especially in the second half, by unprecedented cost jumps for raw milk. `` Fierce competition at the retail level delayed cost recovery in product pricing,'' <PERSON> Borden </PERSON> said.
