<HEAD>Help Wanted Ads Fluctuated In Narrow Range During 1988</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 6:30 p.m. EST.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The volume of help-wanted advertisements in major newspapers rose slightly in December, indicating little change in employers' hiring plans, a business research group said Tuesday. The <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said its Help Wanted Advertising Index rose to 161 last month from 157 in November and 156 in the year-ago month. The board said the index fluctuated in a narrow range throughout the year. The seasonally adjusted index equaled 100 in 1967. The index measures volume of classified ads in 51 major newspapers nationwide and is sensitive to changes in the demand for labor and general business conditions. Conference Board Economist <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON> said, `` The monthly survey data show no change in the labor market conditions that have prevailed for the last year or so. But a change may not be that far off.'' <PERSON> Goldstein </PERSON> predicted there may be a slowing in the job market in 1988 following a year in which unemployment hit a 14-year low.
