<HEAD>Cold Weather, Coming of Lent Affect Futures Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The onslaught of colder weather and an expected drop in meat demand during Lent influenced futures prices for some farm commodities Tuesday, analysts said. Grain and soybean prices were up sharply on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>. Prices were bolstered by unexpectedly high weekly export inspection figures and a report from <ORGANIZATION> Sparks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodities </ORGANIZATION>, a private crop analyst, that pegged <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s soybean crop lower than <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> estimates, said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` A weather forecast calling for bitter cold temperatures in wheat growing areas supported the wheat prices,'' said <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Luth </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Wheat settled 3 \ cents to 6 -RCB- cents higher, with the contract for delivery in March at $ 4.40 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 3 -RCB- cents to 7 \ cents higher, with March at $ 2.74 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 6 cents to 6 -RCB- cents higher, with March at $ 2.21 -RCB- a bushel; and soybeans were 4 cents to 12 -RCB- cents higher, with March at $ 7.72 -RCB- a Livestock and meat futures prices were mostly higher on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Cash prices were helpful for both cattle and hog futures, said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gidel </PERSON>, general analyst with G.H. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, but enthusiasm was limited by the propect of diminished consumer demand for meat during Lent, a 40-day religious period which begins Feb. 8. `` The cold weather forecast has been a factor in the marketplace,'' said <PERSON> Gidel </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` There should be less farmer movement of animals to market once the colder temperatures set in.'' Cattle settled .10 cent to .42 cent higher, with the contract for delivery in February at 74.72 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .08 cent to .30 cent higher, with March at 84.47 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent to .80 cent higher, with February at 43.35 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .25 cent lower to 1.00 cent higher, with February at 39.52 cents a pound. Precious metal prices were lower for the fourth straight session on the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` The further declines were in response to strong dollar gains, which were accomplished by -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman -RRB- <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>'s anti-inflationary statements to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> today,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Steel </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Gold settled $ 3.70 to $ 4.10 lower, with the contract for delivery in February at $ 391.60 a troy ounce; and silver was 4 cents to 4.4 cents lower, with February at $ 5.79.2 a troy ounce. Energy futures prices fell on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Crude oil settled 16 cents to 26 cents lower, with the contract for delivery in March at $ 17.03 a barrel; and heating oil was .31 cent to .64 cent lower, with February at 52.28 cents a gallon.
