<HEAD>Greenspan Comments Lift Dollar; Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar surged to three-month highs Tuesday after <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit would shrink in coming months without a decline in the dollar's value Gold prices, meanwhile, fell to their lowest level in two years, continuing the downward trend that began last Friday when they broke below $ 400 an ounce. <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> also said that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts to boost interest rates would not lead to a recession, but would extend the current expansion by keeping inflation under control. Currency dealers took the remarks to mean that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> central bank was unconcerned by the dollar's recent rise and was willing to keep interest rates tight, something that would make dollar-denominated investments attractive. `` It was <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> today,'' said <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Curtin </PERSON>, assistant treasurer of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Australia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Testifying before the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> also reiterated his statement of last week that the current rate of inflation is too high and said he expects a further substantial contraction in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. Dealers have been focusing on firm <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates this year rather than the budget and trade deficits that preoccupied them last year. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell 0.60 yen to a closing 129.13. But later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted higher at 129.85 yen. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the dollar rose to 130.13 yen from 129.30 on Monday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost $ 1.7535 to buy one pound, cheaper for buyers than $ 1.7650 late Monday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the pound fell to $ 1.7531 from $ 1.7625. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Monday's levels, included: 1.8767 West German marks, up from 1.8595; 1.5978 Swiss francs, up from 1.5808; 1.1830 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1813; 6.3743 French francs, up from 6.3235; and 1,371.3 Italian lire, up from 1,360.5 Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Monday's levels, included: 1.8710 West German marks, up from 1.8660; 1.5985 Swiss francs, up from 1.5884; 6.3580 French francs, up from 6.3500; 2.1100 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1085; 1,365.00 Italian lire, down from 1,365.50; and, 1.1840 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1820 The price of gold fell sharply in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> after having been little changed earlier in the Far East and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` The -LRB- precious -RRB- metals have just done nothing for so long and they have to test their lows before they can go higher. ... It's a matter of water seeking its proper level,'' said <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Posnick </PERSON>, senior vice president of <ORGANIZATION> MTB </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose 59 cents a troy ounce to close at a bid $ 396.55. Gold fell slightly in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 394.25 a troy ounce, compared with late Monday's $ 394.50. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold was slightly higher, closing at a bid $ 394.20 compared with $ 394.00 late Monday. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery fell to $ 391.60 a troy ounce from $ 395.30 on Monday. Later, <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said gold bullion was bid at $ 390.80 an ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, down from $ 394.35 late Monday. Silver bullion prices rose slightly on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $ 5.85 a troy ounce, compared with Monday's $ 5.83. But on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery fell to $ 5.792 an ounce from $ 5.832 on Monday.
