<HEAD>Energy Prices Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Energy futures prices declined Tuesday due to weather and other factors as investors awaited new statistics on domestic petroleum supplies. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the March contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, fell 26 cents to close at $ 17.03 after falling 45 cents on Monday. Among refined products, the February contract for unleaded gasoline lost 1.16 cents to settle at 47.72 cents a gallon, while domestic heating oil slumped 0.31 cent to a settlement price of 52.28 cents a gallon. The prices of other contract months also declined. Traders said the reopening of the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> pipeline after a partial closing on Monday due to sub-freezing temperatures, contributed to the drop in heating oil prices. Near-month contract prices had jumped on Monday as investors anticipated a surge in demand due to the partial shutdown as well as the blast of cold temperatures that hit the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Heating oil and gasoline prices also lost ground as investors adjusted their positions on the last day of the February contract, analysts said. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiedler </PERSON>, chief energy broker for <ORGANIZATION> E.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Man </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said the decline in crude prices was due partly to technical corrections following several weeks of steadily rising prices since November's agreement by the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> Exporting Countries. The accord, which took effect Jan. 1 and extends for six months, set an oil production quota of 18.5 million barrels a day for the 13 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members. At the time the accord was reached, <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> was producing more than 22 million barrels, far more than the market could absorb. The excess forced prices to the $ 12 range, below the $ 18 benchmark price set by <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>. Traders said they also anticipated a buildup in energy stocks when the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> released its weekly report after the close of trading on Tuesday.
