<HEAD>Xerox Announces Cuts Of 2,000 Jobs; Posts Loss For Quarter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, Xerox stock, to UPDATE with closing price.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, dissatisfied with its earnings, on Tuesday announced a $ 275 million streamlining program under which it will cut 2,000 jobs, trim its electronic typewriter business and stop selling medical image-making equipment. The <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, Conn.-based copier giant said a charge to cover costs of the program was recorded in the fourth quarter of 1988, resulting in a $ 77 million loss for the quarter. Without the pre-tax charge of $ 275 million, profit in the quarter would have risen 8 percent, <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> stock rose 37 -LCB- cents a share to $ 62.37 -LCB- in consolidated <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading. <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> lost money last year in electronic typewriters; document workstations; and medical image-making, which uses an unusual copying process called xeroradiography, according to <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Kearns </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive. `` We are not moving as rapidly toward our objectives as we feel we must,'' <PERSON> Kearns </PERSON> said in a news conference, explaining the streamlining program. The losses were partially offset by a good reception for its new 50 Series of copiers and healthy profits in the financial services business, which accounts for 30 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> revenue, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> said its loss in the fourth quarter contrasted with a profit of $ 155 million, or $ 1.43 a share, a year earlier. Without the charge, it said, profit would have been $ 167 million. Revenue rose 6 percent to $ 4.4 billion from $ 4.15 billion a year earlier. For all of 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> said its earnings fell 33 percent to $ 388 million, or $ 3.50 a share, from $ 578 million, or $ 5.35 a share, a year earlier. Without the fourth-quarter charge, profit would have risen 9 percent to $ 632 million. Revenue rose 9 percent to $ 16.4 billion from $ 15.1 billion. The biggest portion of the fourth-quarter charge, $ 140 million, comes from writing off excess manufacturing capacity at its electronic typewriter plant in <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and disengaging from the <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> business, which is based in <LOCATION> Monrovia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> will continue to provide service and supplies to existing customers of its medical equipment Another $ 100 million of the charge comes from the cost of reducing overhead and employment. <PERSON> Kearns </PERSON> said the company could not yet say how many of the 2,000 job cuts would have to be achieved by layoffs, vs. retirements or voluntary resignations. The jobs that are being eliminated are in staff rather than in sales or manufacturing, <PERSON> Kearns </PERSON> said. The cutbacks in <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Monrovia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, will not involve big job cuts because employment has already been reduced there, <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> said. The company said the market for cheaper and medium-priced electronic typewriters has shrunk much faster than expected, leaving the industry with excess capacity. <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> said it hopes to cure the losses in its document workstation business by gradually dropping its own workstations and switching its software over to industry-standard workstations made by <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microsystems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Separately, <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> said it was reorganizing its management. It said <PERSON> Wayland </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hicks </PERSON>, an executive vice president, will head a new marketing and customer organization. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>, who was hired from <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in December, will head development and manufacturing and <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nussbaum </PERSON> will head a new unit, <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION>.
