<HEAD>7-Eleven To Accept Payment Of Utility Bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Utility customers who do n't pay by mail will soon be able to pay their bills at some 7-Eleven stores. National Payments Network of <LOCATION> Paramus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, said <ORGANIZATION> Southland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s 7-Eleven was the first national chain that had agreed to let the company install computer terminals to handle its electronic payment system. National Payments Network caters mainly to poor and elderly people who pay their utility bills with cash in person rather than sending checks by mail, according to <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, vice president for sales and marketing. Utility companies in 18 states already accept bills paid through more than 2,000 locations where the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Payments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> has outlets. Those are mostly mom' n' pop stores or small, regional chains, <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> said. Four 7-Eleven stores in the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> area have already tested the National Payments Network system. Other markets will be added as time goes on, he said. Since 7-Eleven stores are franchised, some may choose not to participate. Although many supermarkets and other retail outlets accept payment of bills, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Payments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> gets money to billers faster because it is electronic. That can make a difference if a utility customer is threatened with cut-off. In some areas, 50 to 60 percent of all customers pay their utility bills in person, <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Payments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> said in a news release.
