TION> America </LOCATION> acquired the Gulf stations from <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 after <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> purchased <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and sold assets to avoid antitrust problems. It also recently acquired <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> stations in three <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> states that will convert to the BP brand. <ORGANIZATION> BP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> said it plans to redesign some of the service stations according to a new format. <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> said the company `` conducted extensive research, both nationally and internationally,'' before deciding to unify its businesses under one name. He said use of the name `` BP'' in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would provide the company with a `` consistent identity.'' <LOCATION> BP </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, based in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, moved its headquarters from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> after the company purchased controlling interest in Cleveland-based <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> in 1987.
