<FIRST>r f BC-DuPont-Ozone     01-31 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Du Pont-Ozone,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Du Pont Gets Patent for CFC Replacements</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has received a patent on a compound blend that could accelerate the replacement of halogenated chlorofluorocarbons, or CFCs, which damage the earth's ozone layer, a spokesman said Tuesday. The company said the three-component blends of environmentally acceptable compounds will have no adverse effects on the environment, compared to CFC-12, one of the products suspected of depleting the ozone layer. <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> is the largest maker of CFCs in the world and has said it will cease making the chemicals by the end of the century. Scientists say CFCs have the potential to damage the environment, including decreasing the ozone layer, a shield that protects the earth from ultraviolet light. Under the Montreal Protocol treaty, countries producing CFCs have agreed to reduce <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> production by 50 percent by 1998. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has signed the agreement. The new blends could be used for existing medium-temperature food display cases, vending machines, water coolers, home refrigerators and freezers, and automobile air conditioners _ all of which make up about 30 percent of the <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> market in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The new blends would gradually be placed in items that use CFCs as they wear out. `` Otherwise we would not be able to phase out production -LRB- of CFCs -RRB- until all the equipment was off the market,'' said <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> McCain </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> manager of the alternative development program. `` We will still work to find an alternative for new equipment. This would go in parallel with it,'' he said. `` We have received a patent on the technology which says the blend works. But it will take a couple of years to test it in operating systems to define all the changes that might be required in a refrigerator or car and then we have to finish the process development,'' <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> said. The new technology was made public Monday at a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heating </ORGANIZATION>, Refrigeration and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conditioning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineers </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Candidate components for the blends include HCFC-22, HFC-152a and HCFC-124. <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> said HCFC-124 is a new product. `` Mix those three together and you get something very close to what we had with CFC-12 as far as performance,'' he said. <PERSON> McCain </PERSON> said the blends were more energy efficient than HFC-134a, the leading single-product candidate alternative for CFCs. <PERSON> Du </PERSON> <PERSON> Pont </PERSON> plans to introduce a series of alternative products in a three - to five-year period beginning in 1990 Complete phaseout of CFCs may take until the turn of the century, the company said.
