<HEAD>From Halfway Around the World Dealers Came to See What's New</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Car dealers from both sides of the world have some straightforward advice for their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> friends _ learn how to sell used cars. More than 100 auto dealers and manufacturers representatives from 16 foreign countries were among thousands of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automobile dealers who attended the 72nd annual convention of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which ended Tuesday. Visiting dealers from <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, with almost the same words, said they were struck by how little attention <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dealers paid to selling cars that have some miles on them. `` You have no idea how to sell a used car,'' said <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> dealer from <LOCATION> Melbourne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. `` I think we can teach the Americans how to sell them.'' `` I think we can sell a used car better than you can,'' said <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON> <PERSON> Winter </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> dealer from <LOCATION> Newcastle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. In separate interviews, White and Winter said used-car sales make up half or more of their dealership volumes, and speculated that the difference may be because <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> drivers do n't treat their cars as well. <ORGANIZATION> NADA </ORGANIZATION> figures show that used-car sales accounted for 6.3 percent of all vehicle sales in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1987, the latest year for which figures are available. Two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> auto dealers said the proliferation of used-car auction houses and used-car businesses not affiliated with a franchised operation is probably the reason. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bayer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Dudley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, who sells <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Cadillac </ORGANIZATION> and Oldsmobile cars, said there was discussion at the <ORGANIZATION> NADA </ORGANIZATION> convention about preparing a car for resale. <ORGANIZATION> Bayer </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Grindstaff </PERSON>, owner of <PERSON> Grindstaff </PERSON> <PERSON> Chevrolet </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Elizabethton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, said in interviews that the condition of a trade-in is a major consideration of whether the car is kept on the dealer's used-car lot or sold elsewhere. Prices also are a big difference in cars sold in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and overseas, the dealers said. Governmental regulations and duties jack up the prices of cars in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> sometimes by 100 percent, <PERSON> White </PERSON> said. He added the regulations also make some vehicles too expensive for him and his fellow dealers to handle. `` We'd love to have these vans,'' <PERSON> White </PERSON> said after seeing some of the customized van conversion displays on the <ORGANIZATION> NADA </ORGANIZATION> show floor. `` But you ca n't get them in.''
