<HEAD>Contracting For New Construction Rebounds 8 Percent In December</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Contracting for new construction rebounded 8 percent in December, marking a departure from the general sluggishness of 1988, according to a report Tuesday. `` Despite its strong finish, 1988 was a year of generally softening construction activity, as the value of all newly started work fell 2 percent short of the 1987 peak,'' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>, vice president and chief economist of F.W. <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement. <PERSON> Christie </PERSON> said the 1988 decline ended a five-year period of continuously expanding construction contracting. He predicted the market would decline again this year. The big factors in the drop were overbuilt commercial properties and limited public funding, according to F.W. Dodge, a unit of <ORGANIZATION> McGraw-Hill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. An additional factor this year is higher interest rates, <PERSON> Christie </PERSON> said Construction of highways and other public works projects contributed to an 18 percent increase in the non-building category in December over November. For the year, the category fell 1 percent from 1987. Residential building rose 7 percent in December but was about even for the year. Contracting for non-residential buildings rose 4 percent in December but was down 5 percent for the year. By region, contracting fell 4 percent in the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, held even in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> region, fell 4 percent in the South and rose 2 percent in the West, F.W. <PERSON> Dodge </PERSON> said.
