<HEAD>Robert Bass Busiest Of Wealthy Brothers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Houghton Mifflin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The billionaire Bass brothers are often described as classic passive investors, but their business ventures have kept them among the nation's 400 richest people. The Bass dynasty traces its roots to the forays of wildcatter <PERSON> Sid </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, who made a series of successful oil strikes in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Upon his death in 1959, he willed most of his money to his partner and nephew, <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>. After vastly expanding <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>'s holdings, <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> retired in the late 1960s and left the family empire to his four sons, who each inherited $ 2.8 million. They combined assets to form <ORGANIZATION> Bass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION>, which was managed by eldest son, <PERSON> Sid </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>. With bold moves from the oil patch into stocks and real estate, the brothers added to their collective and individual fortunes. Among their most lucrative ventures, the Basses netted an $ 850 million capital gain after helping to thwart a 1985 takeover fight for <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Also that year, the family liquidated <ORGANIZATION> Bass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION>, its primary investment vehicle, and divided the assets four ways, freeing the brothers to cut some individual deals Since then, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> has focused much of his energy on the information sector. In 1985, he led a group that made a $ 205 million investment in Cincinnati-based <ORGANIZATION> Taft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> that was worth $ 718 million two years later. He and two other shareholders divided <PERSON> Taft </PERSON>'s assets, with the Bass group getting $ 157.5 million in cash, a television station in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and two large cable television properties. In 1988, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> was instrumental in prying away the <LOCATION> Westin </LOCATION> hotel chain from <ORGANIZATION> Allegis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 1.53 billion. In March, he sold the Plaza Hotel in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> to fellow billionaire <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> for $ 410 million. Last May 17, he reached an agreement to purchase <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Howell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a publishing information services company in <LOCATION> Skokie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>. On the same day, a group that he led proposed to buy <ORGANIZATION> Macmillan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION> The move put the publishing giant in play and it was acquired last fall by British publisher <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> for $ 2.5 billion and gave the <ORGANIZATION> Bass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> a gain of about $ 75 million on its holdings before expenses. Most recently, the <ORGANIZATION> Bass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> put up $ 350 million for the bailout of insolvent <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The brothers zealously guard their privacy, persistently refusing interviews and shunning transactions that would require much financial disclosure. They have been described as atypical <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> tycoons with their conservative style and reserved manner. In <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, they are universally revered for their civic investments. <PERSON> Sid </PERSON> is director of the generous <PERSON> Sid </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> Foundation. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> often described as the family maverick, has been more interested in arts and environmental projects. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> is working with <PERSON> Sid </PERSON>, while <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> has taken an interest in some political projects. `` The big difference in the Basses _ and most people like the Basses _ is that they're really not looking for any credit for what they do. They do it because they think it's what they should do and what's good,'' said <PERSON> Dee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> lawyer and longtime family friend. Despite their financial muscle, the Basses are n't the strong-arming type, preferring to work with the management of target companies, as they did in the Disney situation, <PERSON> Checchi </PERSON> noted.
