<HEAD>Foreign Investment in U.S. Setting New Records</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which soared to a record of $ 58.1 billion reported in 1987, is set to go even higher for 1988 according to <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Apcar </PERSON>, director of investment analysis at the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. `` How much the increase will be depends on the data we're still collecting for the last few months of the year,'' he said in an interview Tuesday. `` It was about $ 30 billion for the first half of 1988, and I'd guess about $ 20 billion for the first half of 1987. Actual investment figures are much larger. For more than half the deals reported the department could not find any figure at all. The biggest takeover in 1988 was the acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION>, the fifth largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> retailer, by <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. That was about $ 6.6 billion. In 1987 <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> spent nearly $ 8 billion for the 45 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> that it did not already own. That put the total of British acquisitions for the year at $ 21.2 billion. Figures were identified for only 117 of the 249 transactiona. As has been the case for the past three years, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> was the most active investor with 490 separate deals. Of these, 235 carried idenifiable prices totalling 13 billion. `` While <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> will continue to be the source for most Asian investments for the foreseeable future, it is interesting to note that other Asian-Pacific investors, especially from <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, have increased their activity here -- the number of transactions doubled and the value quadrupled in 1987,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report. It was issued last Friday. `` Foreign investment makes an important contribution to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy,'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON>, named by President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as his top economic adviser, said last week. `` By helping to build productive plant and equipment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, foreign investment contributes to current and future increases in jobs, productivity and growth ... `` Concerns about foreign ownership are somewhat exaggerated. By the end of 1987, measured net foreign assets in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> amounted to some 3.1 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> netwealth on an historical cost basis.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report said the trend toward the growth of foreign investment began in 1983, with the recovery from the recession of the previous two years. The total number of deals had peaked at about 1,200 in 1981 and then dropped sharply. In 1987 the total was 1,328, with values reported for 588 of them. That was an increase of 26 percent over the year before. The report attributed the big rise since 1983 to: _ The drop in the international price of the dollar after 1985, which made it cheaper for foreigners to buy in this country _ Eagerness by many <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> firms to become more profitable and avoid takeovers by getting rid of divisions and subsidiaries they no longer wanted _ Tthe belief by foreign investors that they must invest in the world's largest consumer market in order to stay competiive in <PERSON> Boskin </PERSON> said that although the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has become a debtor country -- with larger assets owned here by foreigners than Americans own in other countries -- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> direct investment in actual property and equipment remains greater than foreign direct investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The figures are reversed when indirect investments such as stocks and bonds are tasken into account.
