<HEAD>GM, Bias Plaintiffs Announce Preliminary Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and lawyers representing thousands of black employees in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> announced Tuesday they had tentatively settled a bias suit against the automaker that could give the plaintiffs payments totaling $ 3 million. The two sides agreed upon a proposed consent decree to end the case, but <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> did not admit it had discriminated against blacks in promotions and pay raises, company spokeswoman <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Molloy </PERSON> said. The proposal provides for distribution of $ 1.6 million to about 2,800 former <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> employees, and raises averaging $ 1,000 a year for about 1,000 current employees, plaintiffs' attorney <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> said. <PERSON> James </PERSON> told a news conference the proposed decree also requires five years of monitoring to ensure that black salaried employees get their fair share of promotions and pay increases. <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, another attorney for the plaintiffs, said the tentative agreement `` reaffirms the importance of class-action civil rights litigation, especially in the current unfriendly political climate towards civil rights in general.'' The suit, filed in 1983 by four employees, was a class action on behalf of 10,000 salaried black employees who worked for <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> between 1982 and 1986 in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. Those states were chosen for the suit because <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> employees there made a manageable-sized group for the legal action, and because <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> plants and offices in those states account for 75 percent of the company's salaried employees, <PERSON> James </PERSON> said. Members of the class will be notified of the proposed agreement over the next two weeks and be given a chance to lodge any objections they may have. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Feikens </PERSON> then will schedule a hearing on whether the decree should be approved, <PERSON> James </PERSON> said. The decree was submitted to <PERSON> Feikens </PERSON> about two weeks ago and <PERSON> Feikens </PERSON> gave his preliminary approval Tuesday, <PERSON> James </PERSON> said. `` This will help blacks to achieve a more equitable position in upper management and also middle management,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, one of the four original plaintiffs. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, now pastor of <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carmel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Flint </LOCATION>, was employed at <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> AC </ORGANIZATION> sparkplug subsidiary in <LOCATION> Flint </LOCATION>. He told the news conference that after starting in 1956, he worked his way up from janitor to supervisor of warehousing and shipping at the AC plant, but found that whites had better paychecks and higher job expectations. Also present were two other original plaintiffs, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodson </PERSON>, sales engineer at <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Allison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transmission </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary in <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kitchen </PERSON>, an employee of <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s Chevrolet-Pontiac-GM of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> group in <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, who both reported similar experiences The fourth plaintiff, <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Huguley </PERSON>, formerly on <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s design staff in <LOCATION> Warren </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, left <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> for a job with <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Benz </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> said.
