<FIRST>u f AM-FAAOrder 1stLd-Writethru   01-31 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FAA Order, 1st Ld-Writethru,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>FAA Issues Order Affecting 741 Boeing Airliners</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with previous British inspections, Boeing spokesman,
inserting 2 grafs after 6th graf, Authorities had</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal aviation officials ordered airlines Tuesday to inspect all of four types of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> airliners built in the last eight years after wiring mix-ups were found on four more planes. In its most far-reaching order to date on the possibility of cross-wiring and cross-plumbing in airline safety systems, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> gave airlines 25 days to complete the testing of both engine and cargo hold safety systems in 741 aircraft. `` This will easily affect most airlines,'' said <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON>. The inspections were ordered for 472 <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s, 33 Jumbo 747s, 123 757s and 113 767s manufactured after Dec. 31, 1980. Previous <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> orders prompted by the discovery of fouled-up wiring or plumbing in several <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> aircraft throughout the world were limited only to plumbing and wiring on individual types of airliners. Wiring and plumbing problems became the subject of <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> orders after British authorities speculated the pilot of a British <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> 737 was deceived into shutting down his only good engine in a crash that killed 44 people in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> Jan. 8. Authorities have not concluded what caused both engines to be shut down in the British plane, but since the crash, cross-wiring of engine or cargo hold fire warning systems has been found in other planes. Inspections ordered earlier by British authorities covered <ORGANIZATION> Airbus </ORGANIZATION> A320s as well as <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s, but faulty wiring has been found only in <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> aircraft, all of which are built in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiminez </PERSON> said the aircraft builder had no immediate comment on the latest order. Officials of <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> and several airlines had said they agreed with previous orders as prudent measures to ensure safety. The newly ordered tests are not expected to disrupt airline schedules and can be completed anytime over the next 3 -LCB- weeks while the airliners are undergoing routine maintenance. Under the `` airworthiness directive'' issued by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> office, airlines are ordered to repair and report any defects to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said the four additional problems were found either during work done under previous directives or in independent testing by airlines. They included faulty wiring on three 757s, he said, including one case of an incomplete circuit that would have kept a fire extinguisher from operating and two cases of cross-wiring. One would have indicated the wrong engine was overheating and the other would have set off the fire extinguisher to the wrong engine, <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said. The fourth case involved cross-wiring that would have indicated fire in the wrong engine of a 737, he said. <PERSON> Farrar </PERSON> said that while foreign airlines flying <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> aircraft are not required to follow the directives, most of them will conduct the tests.
