<HEAD>Eds: Top 4 grafs new to update, picks up into 2nd graf previous ``Things
are''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Banks and savings institutions were braced Tuesday for a possible proposal from the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to raise their insurance premiums as a way to rescue the government fund that insures savings and loan associations. A White House official said Tuesday night the prevailing thought in the administration is that such an approach `` is one of the more attractive'' solutions. The official, speaking on condition of anonymity said that increased risk for the insurer should translate into higher premiums for the institutions. White House officials were convened in a meeting late Tuesday by chief of staff <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> in a meeting that focused on what recommendations to make to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on the S & amp; L situation. ` Things are a little scary to us,'' said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Guenther </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Guenther </PERSON> said he interpreted comments over the weekend by <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON> as indicating the administration was backing away from its controversial suggestion that depositors pay a fee of about 25 cents on every $ 100 in their accounts. Meanwhile, several members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> called for a quick infusion of $ 2 billion into the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> so that regulators could liquidate more insolvent S & amp; Ls while <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> debates proposed reforms. <PERSON> Sununu </PERSON>, responding to questions in a Sunday television interview, had defended the deposit fee idea as if he were talking about an increase in the premium that institutions have been paying since 1934. He `` seemed to be moving away from a deposit fee to an increase in banks' premiums,'' <PERSON> Guenther </PERSON> said in an interview. Senior administration officials are saying they will urge President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to propose a premium hike rather than a fee aid by depositors, according to Tuesday's editions of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, which cited unidentified sources, and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> intends to present at least an outline of his <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L plan when he addresses <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Feb. 9. So far he has indicated no preference among the many options. `` If I were to make a prediction, my guess is those premiums are going up,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramm </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>. `` Somebody's going to end up having to pay them. My guess is it will probably be the institutions, but the depositors will pay them indirectly. `` We'll bury this -LRB- deposit fee -RRB- proposal on the one hand and dig it up through another hole,'' he said. The administration has told members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> it likely will propose selling bonds for about $ 45 billion. The difficulty comes in raising the $ 7 billion to $ 9 billion needed each year to pay off the bonds. The S & amp; L industry and many members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> advocate using tax money, an alternative the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is trying to avoid. <PERSON> Guenther </PERSON> said an increase in premiums for both banks and <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls would be unfair because about two-thirds of the money generated for <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls would come from banks. He estimated that a 25-cent increase in banks' 8.3-cent premium would push as many as 750 profitable banks into the red. To the extent that banks and <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls pass on the cost to their customers through lower interest rates on deposits, it would encourage depositors to put their money in uninsured money market mutual funds offered by brokerage firms, he said. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION>, the largest S & amp; L trade association, has said it can not pay more toward the <ORGANIZATION> FSLIC </ORGANIZATION>'s problems and at the same time raise more capital from investors as a buffer between losses and insured deposits. At the congressional hearings, Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., noting an estimate that insolvent S & amp; Ls are losing $ 1 billion a month, said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should give regulators about $ 2 billion immediately so they can liquidate some institutions rather than rescuing them with promissory notes and loss guarantees `` I have to believe that an immediate infusion of about $ 2 billion for the next six months or so would save us money in the long run,'' he said. Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, agreed, saying, `` It's probably going to be six, seven, eight months at best'' until <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> acts on a reform package. Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif., while not specifically backing <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>'s proposal, said, `` I think we have to consider acting more rapidly. The committee chairman, Sen. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON>, D-Mich., is against spending any money on the problem without tying it to reforms needed to prevent the problem from reoccurring But he said regulators were free to ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for more money. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Fulwider </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, said the agency would wait until the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration presented its proposal before deciding whether to ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for interim financing. The bank board has already advocated that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> allow it to speed up the sale of the remaining $ 5 billion in previously authorized bonds rather than spread the borrowing through 1990, as now required.
